<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belarus Moves to Soften Stance on Drozdy Compound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Belarussian government is taking
conciliatory steps to ease tension with foreign embassies over
their residences in the Drozdy compound.
</P>
<P>
Belarussian Deputy Foreign Minister Vladimir Gerasimovich said
in Minsk Thursday that foreign embassies are no longer under an
ultimatum to move out of their residences.
</P>
<P>
Instead, a special commission has been set up to find a
solution that serves the interests of both Belarus and the foreign
missions.
</P>
<P>
He said the Drozdy compound was the official residence of
Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko and new residences
would be provided for the foreign missions, taking into
consideration their demands.
</P>
<P>
Gerasimovich said foreign embassy staffers "have reacted to
the new situation with understanding", the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He quoted French, German, and U.S. diplomats as saying that
they would leave Drozdy only if the new premises proved acceptable.
</P>
<P>
About 10 meetings with foreign embassy officials were scheduled
on Thursday in search of a comprise, Gerasimovich said.
</P>
<P>
About two months ago, the Belarussian authorities asked foreign
missions in the exclusive compound to vacate their residences, a
move which angered many ambassadors who accused Minsk of violating
the Vienna Convention.
</P>
<P>
In mid-June, the ambassadors of the U. S., the European Union
countries, Poland and Japan were recalled for consultations with
their foreign ministries, plunging Minsk's ties with those
countries to a low point.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Belarussian Foreign Ministry issued a new
notice that the foreign embassies remove their furnishings before
noon Wednesday, but the decision was later revoked.
</P>
<P>
Belarussian relations with the West have been rocky in recent
years and Lukashenko has attributed it to Minsk's closer
integration with Russia and its staunch opposition to NATO's
eastward expansion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
