<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Defies U.N. Embargo to Fly to Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Thursday, defying a U.N. air embargo, flew to Libya to meet
Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi, the Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak flew across the Egyptian-Libyan border and arrived at
noon at the Al-Abrak civilian airport in Al-Bayda, 770 kilometers
east of Libyan capital Tripoli, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The flight was not announced in advance, and Mubarak returned
to Cairo several hours later.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is the most senior world leader to defy the air
embargo, which was imposed in 1992 after Libya refused to hand
over two Libyans involved in the 1988 bombing of an American
airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, that killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
From Al-Abrak, Mubarak drove to Al-Bayda where he met with
Gaddafi, who was recovering from a surgery to repair a hip bone he
broke Monday while exercising.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi was sitting in a wheel-chair when he met with Mubarak,
who inquired about the Libyan leader's health.
</P>
<P>
No reason was given for the visit, but it is believed that
Mubarak went to libya to wish Gaddafi a speedy recovery from the
surgery.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak Wednesday offered to send a medical team to help Libyan
doctors treat Gaddafi's fractured hip bone.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has visited Libya many times since 1992, but the
president always flew from Cairo to somewhere near the
Egyptian-Libyan border and then drove across it, abiding by the
U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
With the flight, the Egyptian president pioneered in defying
the U.N. embargo against Libya.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Organization of African Unity adopted a
resolution, urging member states to ignore the air embargo from
September 1. The Arab League said it is considering to follow suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
