<HEADLINE> Three-Nation Joint Military Exercise Concludes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan, Russia and Kyrgyzstan
Wednesday wound up their two-day joint military exercise
Dostyr-98, which centered on the rapid rescue of hostages and
possible military conflicts in border areas.
</P>
<P>
The Kazak Telegraph Agency reported that in the exercise, the
first of its kind, the military forces of the three countries
fulfilled the principle of joint defense and joint attack as well
as coordinated actions of multiple military forces at the outbreak
of an invasion.
</P>
<P>
The first day of the exercise staged a scene where bandits took
over a train and held the passengers hostages. The military
defeated the bandits through coordination.
</P>
<P>
The allies demonstrated, in the second stage of the exercise,
the ability to take coordinated action when massive military
conflicts occurred in the border areas.
</P>
<P>
The exercise was directed by the Kazak General Chief of Staff
and the first Deputy Defense Minister Hahytjan Ertaev, and led by
Russian Deputy General Chief of Staff Aleksandr Skvorzov and
Kyrgyz General Chief of Staff and first Deputy Defense Minister
Esen Topoenv.
</P>
<P>
Kazak presidential Advisor Tohtar Auhakirov and Kazak Defense
Minister Mukhtar Altynbayer who watched the exercise spoke highly
of its outcome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
