<HEADLINE> Operating Oil Rigs Down 60 Percent in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Low crude oil prices and rainy
weather have led to a 60 percent plunge in the number of drilling
rigs operating across Western Canada, a report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The summer slump is the worst to hit the drilling sector since
1993, when collapsing natural gas prices forced producers to cut
capital spending.
</P>
<P>
The number of rigs working this week was only 176, compared
with 435 in the same period last year, according to Canada's
leading newspaper the Globe and Mail.
</P>
<P>
Wet weather in June and early July left many fields too soft
for rigs to cross, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Numerous projects have been cancelled because of the depressed
oil prices.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, light oil averaged 15.42 U.S.
dollars a barrel, down 28 percent from 21.56 dollars in the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Prices for heavy oil have fallen even harder, off more than 40
percent in the past year for the heavier grades, which are
fetching less than seven dollars a barrel, according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
