<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1630 GMT, July 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- More than 20 people were burnt alive and about
forty others injured Thursday in a fire caused by a head-on
collision between two passenger buses in central Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The accident took place near Vihari, about 350 kilometers
southwest of Pakistan's Punjab provincial capital of Lahore,
according to a report of the Associated Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
A passenger bus was heading towards Kasur, about 50 kilometers
south of Lahore, from Multan, about 460 kilometers southwest of
the capital, when it collided head-on with a bus coming from the
opposite direction, said the report. (Pakistan-Road Accident)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Talks between British Prime Minister Tony Blair and
senior Northern Ireland Orangemen failed Thursday to achieve a
breakthrough in a tense five-day stand-off in Portadown, west of
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Protestant leaders refused to back down from their insistence
that Orange Order members be allowed to parade their traditional
route through a Roman Catholic housing estate in the town.
</P>
<P>
The growing sectarian tension has prompted concern that the
implementation of the April 10 peace pact could be jeopardized as
political aspirations for peace are clouded by the continuing
unrest. (Britain-Blair-Orangemen)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Six people were killed and 98 others injured
Thursday in a strong explosion in the most famous market in
Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported the blast took
place in the Misir Market at 14:00 local time (1100 GMT) and six
people died soon after being rushed to various hospitals for
treatment.
</P>
<P>
Turkish sources, who asked not to be named, told Xinhua that
explosion may be caused by a gas leak, although police are
investigating whether it was a bomb attack by rebel groups.
(Turkey-Blast)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- A team of foreign pathologists have arrived here to
help find the real cause of the death of Nigeria's number one
political detainee Moshood Abiola.
</P>
<P>
The pathologists come from Britain, the United States and
Canada at the invitation of the Nigerian government to involve in
the examination of the corpse of Abiola, who died apparently of
heart attack Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government Tuesday announced the sudden death of
Abiola after he was taken ill during a meeting "which was being
held by Nigerian and United States officials with him".
(Nigeria-autopsy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- NATO will act over the Kosovo issue unless Belgrade
accepts the Contact Group's ceasefire demand, German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel made the remarks after arriving at the Rinas airport in
Tirana.
</P>
<P>
He said Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic would and should
accept the Contact Group's ceasefire demand, made at the Bonn
conference Wednesday, as a first step toward the settlement of the
Kosovo issue. (Albania-NATO-Kosovo) 
</P>
</TEXT>
