<HEADLINE> Israel Allows Visits to Lebanese Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 9 (Xinhua) -- After a 10-month ban, Israel on
Thursday allowed Lebanese to visit their relatives jailed in its
prison in the occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four Lebanese traveled to Nabatieh, a central city near
south Lebanon, on a coach provided by the International Committee
of the Red Cross (ICRC), the Orient Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
From there, they walked to the Kfar Tibnit crossing point on
the edge of the zone where they were reunited with 21 prisoners
jailed in Khiam prison.
</P>
<P>
The excited prisoners told the radio that they were grateful to
the ICRC for arranging the visits. They also called on the
Lebanese government to make efforts to secure the release of all
Lebanese prisoners in Israel.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that there are at least 75 Lebanese detainees
remaining in the Khiam prison and another 42 in prisons inside
Israel.
</P>
<P>
During the recent swap between Lebanon and Israel brokered by
the ICRC, Israel already released 60 Lebanese prisoners and
returned bodies of 40 killed guerrillas in exchange for the
remains of an Israeli soldier killed in south Lebanon last year.
</P>
<P>
Israel has created a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in
south Lebanon since 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its
north from cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The Khiam prison, run by Israel's allied South Lebanese Army
(SLA), is used to jail the captured members of anti-Israeli
resistance guerrilla groups and those who refuse to collaborate
with Israel or the SLA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
