<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Opposition UNIP to Take Part in Local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Elections
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's former president Kenneth
Kaunda, leader of the United National Independency Party (UNIP)#,
reiterated Thursday that his party will participate in the
forthcoming local government elections.
</P>
<P>
While reading a statement approved by the largest opposition
party's Central Committee at a news conference held in Lusaka,
Kaunda said the decision was affirmed during a three-day
closed-door meeting ending Monday to discuss his declared
retirement from the party presidency.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda told hundreds of diplomats, reporters and UNIP cadres
that his party, which boycotted the 1996 general elections, will
prepare themselves adequately for the elections and they will
"fight to win."
</P>
<P>
He urged the Zambian govenment to conduct a fresh
registration of voters to ensure that all the eligible voters are
registered, saying that the country's Electoral Commission should
be "truly independent."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the UNIP Central Comittee decided to take
part in the forthcoming local government elections to be held
later this year.
</P>
<P>
As for the issue of Kaunda's retirement from the party
presidency, the statement said the UNIP National Council will
meet to consider it and that if necessary, an extraordinary
congress will be held to make a final decision.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was released on June 1 after five months of detention
for alledged involvement in the country's foiled military coup
last October.
</P>
<P>
He later declared at a news briefing that he is seriouly
considering quitting from Zambia's active party politics.
</P>
<P>
His retirement is believed to be part of a package concluded
between the govenment and Kaunda's family to set the 74 year-old
former president free. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
