<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Back Home From 3-Nation Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has returned home Thursday afternoon after a four-day regional
tour which took him to Eritrea, Ethiopia and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
His trip to the Horn of Africa is deemed as a fresh effort
toward ending the armed border conflict between Eritrea and
Ethiopia, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
During this visit, the president held talks with Eritrean
President Issaias Afeworki, Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi
and South African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
During talks with Eritrean and Ethiopian leaders, Museveni
reiterated Uganda's stance on their border dispute, hoping both
sides can overcome their differences and resolve the issue
through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds have died since the long-running border disagreement
boiled over into a bloody conflict on May 6.
</P>
<P>
There have been no reports of significant fighting since June
11, but witnesses say that both sides have been building up their
troops and artillery along the front line.
</P>
<P>
In Pretoria, Museveni is estimated to have also exchanged
views with Mandela on the Burundi issue, the situation in the
Democratic Republic of Congo and Nigeria as well as the
Ethio-Eritrean border dispute.
</P>
<P>
A South African diplomat was quoted as saying Wednesday that
Museveni is trying to solicit support from the South Africans and
especially President Mandela for a peace initiative aimed at
ending the conflict in the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Museveni was accompanied by First Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister of Foreign Affairs Eriya Kategaya during the visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
