<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Mission to Brief G-8 of Pak Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Paul Chabrier, head of an
International Monetary Fund (IMF) mission, said here Thursday they
will brief both G-8 countries and IMF Executive Board of a major
financial crisis Pakistan is likely to face due to sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint press conference with Pakistani Finance
Minister Sartaj Aziz, Chabrier said he will report to the
executive directors of the G-8 countries Monday in Washington that
unless the ESAF/EFF (Extended Structural Adjustment
Facility/Extended Fund Facility) program is activated quickly,
Pakistan will be left with few options to handle the looming
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Chabrier further said the implementation of economic reforms
program and policy performance was satisfactory and Pakistan had
met all the targets till June 1998, agreed under ESAF and EFF
program.
</P>
<P>
The IMF representative, who is here as head of the IMF
fact-finding mission after Pakistan's detonation of nuclear
devices at the end of May, said the purpose of the current visit
was to assess the changed environment in the wake of sanctions and
response of the government in this peculiar economic situation.
</P>
<P>
"Sending of this mission by the IMF in this respect is quite
normal," he said. "We were not in direct contact with the
authorities when the sanctions were imposed and it is quite normal
that, given the close relationship we have for so many years with
Pakistan, we sent a mission to look at the facts."
</P>
<P>
He said the Pakistani government explained what is the position
and on the basis of these facts this review will be reported to
the IMF management and executive directors on the Board.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said on the occasion that at the time of drawing up the
national budget for 1998-99, it was not indicated if the sanctions
would also apply to international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the current economic deterioration was not
due to any change in underlying fundamentals of the economy which
had, in fact, improved substantially in 1997-98, but due primarily
to exogenous factors, arising from the negative impact of
sanctions on inflows from donors and the resulting crisis of
confidence which is affecting private sector inflows.
</P>
<P>
Suspension of inflows from the IMF as part of the ESAF/EFF will
affect the balance of payments both directly and indirectly as
other multilateral agencies like the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank have also linked their support to the resumption
of the program, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister urged the international financial
institutions to activate program and project financing to Pakistan
as the country has met all conditionalities during 1997-98 fiscal
year set by the IMF.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
