<HEADLINE> Clinton's Advisor to Attend Internet Summit in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Ira Magaziner, senior advisor on
United States Internet policy to President Bill Clinton, will
attend the 1998 Internet summit scheduled on July 21-24 in Geneva,
announced the Internet Society (ISOC) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In his role as the leading U.S. spokesman for Internet policy,
Magaziner will speak at the conference's governance panel. He will
discuss the role of government in determining Internet policy and
provide his perspective on the administration and regulation of
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The annual conference organized by the ISOC provides a forum
for world leaders of the Internet community to discuss the
evolution of the Internet and its future impact on many key areas
of society, including communications, health, law, education and
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
The conference plays an important part in the ISOC's overall
program to encourage global coordination and cooperation on the
Internet, and Magaziner will provide the U.S. government's
perspective on the new era of self-governance upon which the
Internet community is now embarking.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 peer-reviewed papers will be presented during
INET'98. Major sponsors for the event include Geneva Financial
Center Foundation, Compaq Computer Corporation, Sun Microsystems,
Cisco Systems, IBM, France Telecom, University of Geneva and MCI
Communications. 
</P>
