<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Shortage Threatens 38 Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The number of countries facing food
shortage across the world have increased to 38 compared with 31
toward the end of last year, mainly due to the El Nino.
</P>
<P>
Among the countries facing food shortage, 20 are in Africa,
according to the latest issue of Food Outlook published by the
Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO).
</P>
<P>
In Africa, the food shortage has stemmed from the recent
droughts followed by floods im most of eastern Africa, coupled
with civil strife in some of the countries, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In Somalia, the food supply situation will remain extremely
tight until the next harvest beginning next month following the
worst floods in decades. The floods have also resulted in the
loss of livestock and outbreak of animal diseases.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, food assistance continues to be distributed to those
affected by severe floods in the eastern parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Emergency food assistance is still required for some 400,000
displaced people in the north of Uganda affected by continuing
insurgency.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, food shortage is also experienced in some areas
due to heavy rains and floods.
</P>
<P>
In Ethiopia, food aid is needed by over five million people
while in Eritrea, following two successive reduced cereal harvests,
the overall food supply is tight, and food prices have soared up
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Despite an overall satisfactory harvest in Sudan, the food
situation there is critical for some 2.4 million people affected
by civil strifes and droughts. The distribution of food aid are
hampered by insecurity and poor road conditions.
</P>
<P>
In Burundi, the food situation has deteriorated as a result of
a decline in the 1998 first season food crop production and the
continuing economic embargo by neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The food supply situation in Rwanda is also tight due to a
reduced 1998 first season harvest and insecurity in western areas
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural production is improving in Liberia and Sierra
Leone but both still need international food assistance. The
tense security situation in the east and north of Sierra Leone is
leaving large population displaced and is disrupting all
agricultural activities in these areas.
</P>
<P>
Senegal, Mauritania, the Gambia and Burkina Faso, Niger and
the Democratic Republic of Congo are also facing food shortage
due to poor harvests resulted from El Nino or civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
In Zambia, the output of cereals is expected to be much below
average as a result of incessant rainfalls and extensive flooding
in northern areas, while the southern part experienced near
drought conditions.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, grave food supply difficulties persist in the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea. And severe drought in
Indonesia attributed to El Nino, combined with the financial
crisis, has seriously undermined the food security situation.
</P>
<P>
Some other countries in Latin America and the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) are also facing food shortage, said
the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Backs Greece's Proposal on No-Fly Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus said Thursday it supports
Greece's proposal for creating a no-fly zone over the divided
island, terming it as a significant step toward demilitarization.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, government spokesman
Christos Stylianides said: "This position is part of the joint
strategic and tactical policy of Cyprus and Greece."
</P>
<P>
The proposal for creating a no-fly zone over Cyprus was renewed
Wednesday by Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatozopulos during his
meeting in Washington with his U.S. counterpart William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is reportedly pressing Cyprus to refrain from
deploying the Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles in next
month, citing that this would escalate tension in the island.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot government has adopted the Greek proposal for
reaching an agreement on establishing a no-fly zone as part of its
efforts to realize demilitarization of island.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides confirmed a report published Thursday by the Greek
Cypriot daily Philelephtheros that U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides had
exchanged letters on the situation in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The paper said Albright had sent a letter to Clerides
suggesting Cyprus reconsider its plan to buy the Russian
missiles. Albright proposed that the Russian missiles be deployed
outside the island or missiles of a shorter range be deployed
instead.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus ordered the Russian missiles in 1997, which are
scheduled to be deployed next month. The deal angered Turkey and
the Turkish Cypriots, who said their security would be seriously
threatened by the missiles that have a range of 150 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has vowed to strike the missiles if they are deployed
in the island.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides reaffirmed that his government would continue to
stand firm on the missile issue despite the U.S. position.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government has made it clear that it would halt the
deployment of new weapons only if progress is made on formulating
a schedule for the island's demilitarization or in the Cyprus
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks have been stalled since last July when the
Turkish Cypriots quited the talks in protest against the decision
by the European Union (EU) to start accession talks with the
Cyprus government.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots are demanding the recognition of its
self-proclaimed "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in the north
and the halt of the EU talks as preconditions for resuming the
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
