<HEADLINE> Barak Urges Netanyahu to Advance Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli opposition Labor Party
leader Ehud Barak Thursday met with Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and urged him to advance the peace process with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
After a two-hour meeting with Netanyahu, Barak told Israel
Radio that he expressed to the prime minister his deep concern
about the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The talks have been deadlocked for more than a year, first
because of Israel's settlement housing construction in East Arab
Jerusalem and then because of the long overdue Israeli troop
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Barak told Netanyahu that it was time for the government to
reach a resolution on the second redeployment of Israeli troops in
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He also asked Netanyahu to make efforts to reach a peace
agreement with the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) on the
further withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
According to signed agreements between Israel and the
Palestinians, Israel should carry out three phases of pullback
before talks on a permanent peace can begin in mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
Barak noted that after Wednesday meeting he knew more about the
current state of the peace negotiations with the Palestinians,
which have so far been kept secret. Israeli officials have hinted
that an agreement was near.
</P>
<P>
Barak, however, stressed that he did not discuss with Netanyahu
the issue of establishing a national unity government, which was
seen by some politicians as a way to solve the differences in the
Israeli government over the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has been under great pressure from extremists in his
right-wing Likud coalition not to give back any more lands to the
Palestinians. But pressure also came from the U.S. and the
Palestinians, who urged Israel to decide on pullback soon in order
to rescue the falling peace process.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that the formation of a broader-based
government to include the leftists could keep Netanyahu afloat and
pave the way for a deal with the Palestinians on redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Barak and Netanyahu came as the United
States was making intense efforts for an Israeli-Palestinian
agreement. Netanyahu is urged to accept the American peace
proposal calling for an Israeli pullback from 13.1 percent more of
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has conditioned a breakthrough in Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations on what he called the PNA living up to its
commitments to ensure the security of Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
