<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The German carmaker Bayerische Motoren
Werke AG (BMW) announced Thursday that it would stop supplying
engines and other car parts to Rolls-Royce by July 9 next year as
a result of its lost bid to take over the British luxury carmaker.
</P>
<P>
BMW's move came after shareholders of the British Vickers PLC,
the parent company of Rolls-Royce, last month formally approved a
430-million-pound (713-million-U.S. dollar) bid for Rolls-Royce
offered by another German car company, Volkswagen AG, while
turning down the rival bid by BMW.
</P>
<P>
BMW currently supplies about 30 percent of the parts for
Rolls-Royce's new models, including V-12 engines for Silver Seraph
and V-8 engines for Arnage. Executives of the company have
repeatedly threatened to terminate the deliveries during the
fierce bidding war against Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
Volkswagen, however, has promised that it would be able to
develop alternative engines for Roll-Royce. 
