<HEADLINE> Lufthansa Fleet to Be Equipped with New Safety Devices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The German airline Lufthansa announced
Thursday that it would equip its planes with a new safety device
which would be useful mainly to prevent possible plane crashes at
landing or takeoff.
</P>
<P>
The new system is based on a computer databank which keeps a
stockpile of all landscape features. The actual position of a
flying plane will be followed through satellite navigation and
will be compared with the electronic map.
</P>
<P>
Should a collision loom ahead, the on-board device could send a
warning signal to the pilot one minute in advance.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the new system is much better than the
existing Radar-based one which can only send early warning of
about four to eight seconds in advance.
</P>
<P>
Lufthansa said that almost all planes in its fleet would be
equipped with the new system by the year 2001. The costs are
estimated at about 180,000 German marks (100,000 U.S. dollars) for
every plane. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
