<HEADLINE> Cyprus President Backs Bicommunal Business Contacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides
said Thursday that he supports business contacts between Greek and
Turkish Cypriots on the divided island.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark in a meeting Thursday with a group of Greek
Cypriot businessmen who attended a meeting of business
representatives from the two Cypriot communities in Oslo,
Norwegian capital, early this month.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Greek Cypriot businessmen group Constantinos Lordos
told reporters after the meeting that Clerides encouraged them to
continue efforts in pursuing contacts and cooperation with their
Turkish Cypriot counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Clerides also assured them of the government's full support.
</P>
<P>
Lordos said Turkish Cypriot businessmen are also positive in
seeking a relaxation and eventual lifting of all restrictions on
the free movement in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said Greek and Turkish Cypriot businessmen will meet again
on November 16-17 in Istanbul, Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The two-day Oslo meeting, chaired by U.S. Presidential emissary
for Cyprus, Richard Holbrooke, was a follow-up to a meeting in
Brussels in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the Greek and Turkish Cypriot businessmen
agreed to work together on a number of projects such as the
restoration of the Apostolos Andreas Monastery in the Turkish
Cypriot-controlled northeastern Karpass peninsula, and the Halal
Sultan Mosque in the government-dominated southern areas.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot south and
the Turkish Cypriot north since 1974 when Turkey landed troops and
took over the northern third of the island after a failed
pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has reportedly been
restricting the participation of Turkish Cypriots in bicommunal
events since last December, to protest against a decision by the
European Union to begin accession talks with the Cypriot
government in March. 
</P>
