<HEADLINE> Bank of England Leaves Interest Rates Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of England brought some
respite Thursday to business by deciding not to increase interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Bank's Monetary Policy Committee made the
decision after their two days' meeting of leaving rates unchanged
at 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
There was an outcry last month when rates went up by 0.25
percent, prompting fears that the high cost of borrowing and the
strong pound could bring a recession.
</P>
<P>
The announcement sent British stocks and bonds higher and the
pound lower against the mark. The FTSE 100 index of leading shares
reversed earlier losses and rose 0.45 percent. The pound dropped
about a half pfennig to just below 2.98 mark.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in the City believe that the announcement provides
some short-term relief for the UK markets. However, the threat of
another increase has not been removed and the action is likely to
be rather limited.
</P>
<P>
The risk of a further increase in August or September remains
intact, they add. 
</P>
