<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sub-Saharan Warned of Population Explosion, AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Sub-Saharan Africa, compared with
other regions in the world, holds both the fastest growing
population and highest death rates triggered by AIDS, a leading
international body on family planning said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
By mid 1997, sub-Saharan Africa has a population of some 614
million people, making up about 10 percent of the total world
population, Xinhua learned from a regional meeting of the
International Planned Parenthood Federation (IPPF).
</P>
<P>
The region's population growing rate stands at about 2.7
percent per year in 1990s, "faster than that of any other region
in the world," said experts at the two-day meeting which will end
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Death rates are also higher here than elsewhere, and are
rapidly increasing due to the HIV/AIDS pandemic," they warned.
</P>
<P>
They quoted the United Nations Program on AIDS as saying that
last year up to 20.8 million people living in Sub-Saharan Africa
were HIV carriers. HIV is the virus which can cause the fatal
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Rapid urbanization, refugee movements caused by war, economic
distress, environmental disasters, poverty, malnutrition, high
level of illiteracy and limited education and health care are
blamed by the experts on the rampant situation of HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The maternal mortality rate in sub-Saharan Africa, varying
from 600 to 1,500 for every 100,000 births, is also the highest
in the world, the experts quoted the U.N. data as saying.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Fred Sai, the former IPPF president, estimated that there
are at least 150,000 pregnancy-related deaths in Africa each
year, 25 to 50 percent of them resulted from unsafe induced
abortions.
</P>
<P>
The IPPF currently runs family planning projects and health
care operations in more than 30 sub-Saharan African countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
