<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's Air Transport Safety Praised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 9 (Xinhua) --Visiting U.S. Secretary of
Transportation Rodney Slater said here Thursday that Ethiopia's air
transport safety is exemplary to other African air lines.
</P>
<P>
At talks with Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi, Slater
said the Ethiopian airlines are one of four African countries
that met the safety standard of the U.S.Aviation Authority and
has already begun direct flight to Washington DC.
</P>
<P>
Slater is currently travelling in Africa to discuss the ''Safe
Skies Initiative for Africa Program announced by President
Clinton in Senegal during his visit to Africa in March this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, Slater said the
initiative envisages, among others, the tightening of airport
security, enhancing the efficiency of maintenance facilities and
the flight crew as well as the collaborative efforts to be
exerted among governments, air lines, civil aviation authorities
and aircraft manufacturing industries.
</P>
<P>
Slater said he will discuss the initiative with African
ministers at an African air transport safety conference to be
open in Harare on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Transport Ministers from eastern and southern African
countries are expected to sign a convention at the end of the
conference.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Slater Thursday signed here a memorandum of
understanding between the U.S. Trade and Development Agency and
Ethiopian Airlines for technical support worth 100,000 U.S.
Dollars. 
</P>
