<HEADLINE> Egyptian Court Orders Retrial of Killer Nurse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Court of Cassation, Egypt's
supreme court, Thursday ordered a retrial of a nurse sentenced to
death as a serial killer.
</P>
<P>
The court said it made the decision after the appeal judges
found that the the original death sentence was flawed.
</P>
<P>
The nurse, 25-year-old Aida Nourreddine, was sentenced to death
by the Alexandria Criminal Court last March on conviction of
murdering a patient and attempting to murder 29 others in the
Alexandria University Hospital in the second largest city
Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
In the appeal, the defense lawyers argued that the verdict was
flawed because it was based on false confessions which were taken
from her clients under coercion.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution also supported a retrial because the sentence
was based on "probable intention" to kill, which could not be
taken as premeditated murder, and therefore was flawed.
</P>
<P>
After four-hour deliberations, the court ordered a
retrial. Aida was absent from the session but her father fainted
upon hearing the ruling.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 people packed the large hall of the Court of
Cassation in Cairo, mostly of them were lawyers, relatives of the
nurse and representatives of the local, Arab and foreign media.
</P>
<P>
Aida was arrested last August after doctors at the hospital
discovered a pattern in the deaths of 33 intensive care patients
from respiratory failure shortly after they had undergone
successful surgeries.
</P>
<P>
Police investigations found that she injected the patients with
a respiratory muscle relaxant which caused them choke to death.
</P>
<P>
But the former model nurse pleaded innocent all along and
accused doctors at the Neurology Department of negligence by
prescribing wrong medication to their patients.
</P>
<P>
Aida sustained serious broken bones and bruises when she fell
from the third floor of the Prosecution Building where she was
being investigated, the Egyptian English daily Egyptian Gazette
reported. It was unknown if that was her suicide attempt.
</P>
<P>
Her case has sparked accusations in the local media about
widespread malpractice and chaos in Egypt's hospitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
