<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Population to Reach 6 Billion in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- World population will reach
6 billion in 1999, 12 years after it totaled 5 billion in 1987,
according to the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
World inhabitants amount to 5.9 billion today, with an increase
of 3 persons every second, or 222,000 daily or 81 million yearly.
</P>
<P>
Global population reached the 1 billion level by 1800, but it
took 130 years to reach 2 billion by 1930. The number reached 3
billion by 1960 and 14 years later, it grew to 4 billion in 1974.
</P>
<P>
The UNFPA announced Thursday that 16 June 1999 will be observed
as "The day of Six Billion" symbolizing the moment when the world
population passes the 6 billion mark, though the exact landmark
date could not be known for certain.
</P>
<P>
The UNFPA sees it worth celebrating as the 12-year time-span
has sustained the rapidest population growth, when health and
nutritional standards have improved for most of the world's
people, and fertility and family size have fallen faster than ever
before.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion of the U.N.-designated World Population Day,
which falls on July 11, UNFPA Executive Director Nafis Sadik said
that if people can exercise their right to choose the size and
spacing of their family, the world will be on the way to slower
and more balanced population growth.
</P>
<P>
The population group aged 15 and 24, numbering some 1 billion
now, will largely determine the pace of population growth in the
next century, Sadik noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uneasy Calm Prevails in Lagos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Life began to return to normal
slowly in Lagos, Nigeria's business center, following violent
demonstrations triggered by the sudden death of detained
opposition leader Moshood Abiola Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Abiola, the presumed winner of the June 12, 1993 presidential
polls, died of "cardiac arrest" when at a meeting with government
officials and a United States delegation to discuss his release,
according to a government statement.
</P>
<P>
However, some of his relatives and numerous supporters did not
believe that he died a natural death on the eve of release for
political activities which might bring benefit to the people in
the southwest of the country.
</P>
<P>
Many people took to the streets to protest his death and the
demonstrations causing reportedly the death of some 30 people in
the southwestern cities of Lagos and Ibadan as well as Abeokuta,
Abiola's birthplace between the two cities.
</P>
<P>
Some were killed in clashes between law enforcement agents and
hoodlums who took advantage of the demonstrations to loot. The
others died in bloody hand-to-hand battle between two ethnic
groups, the Yorubas of the southwest and the Hausas of the north.
</P>
<P>
The country's Head of State, General Abdulsalam Abubakar, who
sacked the cabinet Wednesday, also appealed to Nigerians to
remain calm.
</P>
<P>
Anti-riot police and soldiers deployed in strategic positions
in Lagos helped bring the situation under control.
</P>
<P>
Markets and offices, many of which closed to guard against
attacks by angry demonstrators since Tuesday night, began to
resume business.
</P>
<P>
More and more vehicles were seen back on the streets in many
parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
While uneasy calmness prevailed in most parts of the
metropolis of eight million people, chaos continued in the
western outskirts and one business district.
</P>
<P>
One man, hawking sugarcane in the Lagos Island business
district, was killed earlier Thursday by irate mobs protesting
against Abiola's death, the News Agency of Nigeria reported.
</P>
<P>
Ibadan is also quiet down although total peace is yet to
return as skirmishes still persisted in some areas of the second
largest city in the southwest, the official news agency said.
</P>
<P>
In Lagos, Ibadan and Abeokuta, schools are closed until
Friday, which is seen by observers as a measure to prevent
students from gathering together.
</P>
<P>
A dusk-to-dawn curfew is also imposed in Abeokuta.
</P>
<P>
But to analysts, the current calm is fragile because the
direct cause of riots still remains untouched unless the
government could provide convincing evidence that Abiola did die
a natural death.
</P>
<P>
Another question facing the government is whether the military
is to to quit office as it has promised years ago.
</P>
<P>
Now a full autopsy of Abiola's body is to be conducted with
the help of some international pathologists, possibly on Friday,
and a report at the end of the exercise will prove whether or not
the government has been honest on the death of the detained
opposition leader.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Provisional Ruling Council, the highest
decision-making body, is meeting for the second day in the
capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which may have ended already by press time, will
produce a detailed new program for the military's transition to
civil rule.
</P>
<P>
People are waiting for the outcome of the autopsy and the
highest meeting to decide what to do next. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
