<HEADLINE> N.Ireland First Minister Warns of Awesome Consequences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's First Minister
David Trimble warned Thursday of "awesome" consequences facing the
province if a stand-off over a banned Protestant parade is not
resolved soon.
</P>
<P>
"Time is running out and this society faces a quite awesome
prospect if between now and the weekend we do not find a
satisfactory way out of it," Trimble told a news conference after
meeting Orange Order leaders in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
"There are elements here who will take advantage of the quite
understandable protest the Orange Order have organized in order to
create mayhem," he added.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said he and Deputy First Minister Seamus Mallon were
still exploring ways of averting a feared showdown on July 13, the
climax of an annual series of marches commemorating William of
Orange, the Protestant king who defeated a Catholic monarch in
1690.
</P>
<P>
Orangemen were banned from the Garvaghy Road by an independent
Parades Commission, which took the decision in an attempt to avert
violence. Since Sunday, thousands of members of the Orange Order
have been confronting police barring them from marching down the
mainly Catholic Garvaghy Road in Portadown.
</P>
<P>
The Portadown stand-off has sparked violence across Northern
Ireland. Police said that since last Saturday there had been 501
attacks on police, including 14 shooting incidents and 29
bombings. Fifty members of the Royal Ulster Constabulary had been
injured.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, talks in London earlier Thursday between British
Prime Minister Tony Blair and leading Orangemen failed to break
the block, as Blair said he was not in a position to reverse the
parade ban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
