<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Pardons All Child Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's child combatants,
estimated at over 4,000, have received a government amnesty,
according to Vice-President Albert Demby, quoted by a report
reaching here Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
Demby made the announcement during the official release of an
annual report by the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF)
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With the amnesty, UNICEF officials say, more than 4,000
children attached to armed groups in the tiny west African
country will not face prosecution for their actions.
</P>
<P>
Demby did not offer details about the nature of the amnesty.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 children have been demobilized from the Sierra
Leone army, disbanded after it was toppled from power in
mid-February, and from militia groups loyal to the current
government as well as from rebels of the Revolutionary United
Front (RUF).
</P>
<P>
Demby also expressed concern over "the increasing rate of
teenage pregnancies, drug abuse, child prostitution and other
social problems which are consequences of eight years of armed
conflict".
</P>
<P>
Civil war was triggered off by RUF in Sierra Leone in 1991 and
peace is yet to be fully restored, despite the reinstatement of
its legitimate government in March after nine months of military
rule.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF representative Anthony Bloomberg urged the government
and civil groups to take the lead to extend "a hand of
reconciliation to RUF children to facilitate their re-integration
into society."  
</P>
</TEXT>
