<HEADLINE> Russia Prods EU on Status as Market Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Russia urged the European Union
Thursday to recognize it as a market economy and ease anti-dumping
sanctions against Moscow.
</P>
<P>
In talks with visiting EU commissioner Hans van den Broek,
Russian officials said the EU's 13 anti-dumping sanctions have
cost Russia an annual 300 million U.S. dollars, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek is on a two-day working visit here. He held talks
with Russian Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko and Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Russia and the EU has been developing rapidly in
recent years. Russian exports to EU countries account for some 40
percent of its total while EU investment in Russia represents half
of foreign investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek, who is in charge of foreign policy of the
European Commission, said his trip is intended to show EU support
for Russia is difficult.
</P>
<P>
He praised the resolve of the Kiriyenko government in
formulating and implementing the anti-crisis program.
</P>
<P>
The Russian press reported that the two sides mainly discussed
the EU's support for Russia's financial and economic
stabilization, expanded exports to the EU and cooperation in
energy, transport, telecommunications and high technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
