<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Ruling Body Meets on Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's ruling body, the
Provisional Ruling Council (PRC), is still meeting on key
national issues including political detainees and a new
transition to democracy timetable.
</P>
<P>
The meeting started at about 3:00 a.m. (local time) Thursday
morning after a joint session of the PRC and all military
administrators, the official News Agency of Nigeria (NAN)
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A member of the PRC, Commodore Anthony Oguguo, told NAN that
the meeting would continue Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting was deliberating on the political
situation of the country with a view of fashioning a direction
for the new military administration led by General Abdulsalam
Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
The agenda also includes the release of all political
detainees as well as the fate of coup convicts, among whom is
Oladipo Diya, the number two leader in the government of late
General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Diya, the Chief of General Staff until his fall, was sentenced
to death by a special military tribunal for alleged involvement
in a coup plot last December. Abacha was expected to approve his
execution before his sudden death of heart attack on June 8.
</P>
<P>
Diya insisted that he was framed up by Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press Wednesday night, Yobe State
Administrator John Ben-Kalio said the joint session of the PRC
and state administrators discussed the suggestions made by
Abubakar on the political future of the country.
</P>
<P>
He said a statement will be issued after the final decision is
made.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria started its transition to civil rule in 1995 under the
Abacha military government.
</P>
<P>
The sudden death of Abacha, who until his passing away was the
consensus candidate of the country's five political parties for
the presidential election scheduled for August 1, has put the
transition program at a cross.
</P>
<P>
Since Abacha's death, the country's opposition has been
demanding the release of and handover of power to Moshood Abiola,
the believed winner of the annulled June 12, 1993 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
But that was made impossible by Abiola's sudden death Tuesday
afternoon, also of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar has been under amounting pressure from both home and
abroad to implement a rapid transition to democracy in the most
populous African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
