<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon has chosen Canadian company Profac to run
its post for 12 years, renewable for another three years, the
Daily Star reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A new company will be set up, with Profac owning two thirds of
its stakes and Lebanese investors holding one third, to mainly
offer service of ordinary and express mail delivery, facsimile,
and sale of stamps.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications will
benefit from mail-handling and facsimile services.
</P>
<P>
Profac is expected to invest 50-90 million U.S. dollars to
modernize the country's postal departments and train postal
employees.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon has signed contracts worth over 1 billion
dollars to rebuild its electricity network devastated during the
1975-1990 civil war, the An-Nahar newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the state-run Council of Development
and Reconstruction said that 47 projects have been signed from
1992 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
Of these, 28 projects have been completed and 19 others are
still under construction.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Bank of Beirut, one of Lebanon's leading banks said
Wednesday that its net income in the first half of this year
reached 6.1 million dollars, up 46 percent from the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
The bank's total assets climbed to 871 million dollars in the
first half of 1998 compared with 643 million dollars in the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Beirut is one of the country's four banks listed on
the Beirut Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus' economy is to grow 4 percent this year as
against last year's 2.3 percent mainly due to an expected 10
percent rise in tourist arrivals, a Central Bank report released
Thursday said.
</P>
<P>
Tourism industry is the pillar of Cyprus economy. A total of
2.06 million foreign visitors visited the Mediterranean island in
1997, with foreign exchange earnings reaching 1.6 billion dollars,
making up 20 percent of the country's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The report said that domestic demand will also recover "as
both consumption and investment expenditures are expected to pick
up in 1998." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
