<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Miners Urged to Guard Against Unskilled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Small-scale miners in
Tanzania have been urged to stop using explosives
indiscriminately so as to avoid more tragedies in work places.
</P>
<P>
Johnbosco Tindyebwa, a government officer dealing with mining
affairs, told people in the Kunduchi Mine here
Thursday that unskilled blasting has caused a lot of deaths and
injuries.
</P>
<P>
Tindyebwa told a seminar that most miners have not received
any training on dynamite blasting and that it is necessary to
form cooperative groups to teach miners relevant knowledge.
</P>
<P>
The Kunduchi mine has over 2,000 illegal miners who are
involved in stone crushing, sand mining and are using dynamite to
blast rocks into gravels. However, none of them has received
professional training for the task.
</P>
<P>
Last month, two miners were killed and a number of others were
injured in the area after a dynamite blasting.
</P>
<P>
The officer appealed to small miners in Bunju, Boko, Mtongani
and Mjimwema areas to refrain from storing dynamite in their
houses because the dangerous practice has violated the law.
</P>
<P>
"It is an offense for an unlicensed miner to store dynamite in
a house," Tindyebwa said.
</P>
<P>
According to Tindyebwa, dynamite blasting during mining has
caused environmental problems and threatened security along the
Bagamoyo Road.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Dar es Salaam City Commission to demolish
houses built in the mining areas since they were built by
squatters.
</P>
<P>
A number of houses which should have been demolished last year
at Kunduchi mines are kept intact while illegal construction of
more houses are underway, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tindyebwa promised to help the mine train four people in order
to curb further killings.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's small-scaled mines are often criticized for their
low safety standard. In April, a landslide resulted from floods
buried alive more than 80 miners in a Tanzanite mine in the
northern region of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state power company TANESCO has found illegal
miners excavating sand under high voltage electric poles with
bags, lorries and caterpillars, ignoring all dangers that may
take place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
