<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-09 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Accuses Greece of Militarizing Aegean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Turkey on Thursday accused Greece of
militarizing its East Aegean islands, which it said seriously
violated international law.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Foreign Ministry again urged Athens
to "comply with the international agreements and define the status
of the islands."
</P>
<P>
This was possibly in reaction to Greece's decision to allow
American warships to make a port call at one of the islands days
ago.
</P>
<P>
It followed a Turkish verbal note of protest last week, which
said the islands should be demilitarized under the 1923 Lausanne
and 1947 Paris treaties.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of World Wars I and II, the east Aegean islands
were left to Greece under the condition that they should never be
militarized. The was aimed at providing Turkey security since the
they are only several miles away from the Turkish shores.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry claimed in the statement that Greece has
been militarizing the islands since the 1960s and continued to do
so "putting as a pretext the 1974 Turkish intervention to Cyprus
and the establishment of the (Turkish) Aegean battalion."
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been locked in disputes over territory,
Aegean sea-bed mineral resources as well as the Cyprus problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
