<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Say Alcohol Could Lower Vitamin B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- One or two alcoholic drinks a
day can interfere with vitamin B levels, according to a study by
scientists at the American Agricultural Research Service.
</P>
<P>
The study of 41 men and women suggests that the blood levels
of vitamin B12 dropped when alcohol made up 5 percent of their
daily calories. Over the long term, compromising B12 status could
impair memory.
</P>
<P>
Scientists also evaluated the volunteers' levels of folate.
This kind of vitamin B helps transform an artery-damaging amino
acid, homocysteine, into a harmless substance. That's important
to health, because high homocysteine is linked with increased
risk of heart disease and stroke. Average blood folate levels
didn't drop when the volunteers were consuming the equivalent of
two drinks a day. But during their alcohol-free period, folate
levels rose and homocysteine levels fell. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Defense Force Urged to Uphold Valour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi Thursday called on the country's defense force to uphold
its valour to shatter and evict the invading Eritrean army.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Ethiopian television, Meles said
Ethiopia has developed its capacity and could bear the burden of
war thanks to the development activities carried out over the
past seven years, the official Ethiopian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Youngsters from the relatively backward regions, not among the
strongholds of the Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Democratic
Front (EPRDF), have volunteered to join the army and some have
caused disturbances due to their failure to meet the requirements
for conscription, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The attempt by the Eritrean army to beat the Ethiopian defense
force in a situation where it could not receive provisions and
other support has failed, the prime minister said, adding that
the defense force has buried 1,800 corpses of the enemy at the
Tekeze front alone.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia, Meles said, will come out victorious if war becomes
inevitable for there is a structural framework put in place at
all levels to properly direct and channel to this end all human
and material resources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a report reaching here Thursday said Eritrean
President Isaias Afwerki said Wednesday that his country will
never withdraw from Badme on the contested border with Ethiopia
and is ready to go to war if necessary.
</P>
<P>
"Even if the sun doesn't rise, we will never withdraw from
Badme," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will try to negotiate but if the war is not resolved soon
we will take the unwanted steps, which will have consequences. It
may be dangerous but we will take the necessary action," Isaias
warned.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea rejected last month a U.S.-Rwanda four-point plan
which called on Eritrean forces to withdraw from contested
territories to the positions held before May 6 when the conflict
began. The U.S.-Rwanda initiative was endorsed by the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and supported by the U.N.
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
After the peace initiative made by the presidents of Burkina
Faso, Zimbabwe and Rwanda as well as the foreign minister of
Djibouti who shuttled between Asmara and Addis Ababa in June, an
OAU ambassadors committee visited both Eritrea and Ethiopia and
will present a report to some African leaders soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
