<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Mortgage Rates Drop to Lowest in Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. 30-year mortgage rates
declined to the lowest level in six months, Freddie Mac, the U.S.
mortgage company, announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The average for 30-year fixed-rate mortgages dropped to 6.91
percent, down from 6.98 percent in the week earlier, marking the
lowest level since rates hit a four-year low of 6.89 percent in
mid-January.
</P>
<P>
Mortgage rates hit a high of 7.22 percent in late April this
year, but have slipped since then.
</P>
<P>
Freddie Mac economist Frank Nothaft predicted that low rates
should hold through the Summer buying season. With various signs
that the U.S. economy is slowing to a more sustainable rate, many
analysts are predicting that the Federal Reserve will be content
to leave short-term interest rates unchanged for the rest of this
year.
</P>
<P>
"It looks as though 1998 will register the lowest annual
mortgage rate in 30 years," Nothaft noted.
</P>
<P>
The Freddie Mac weekly report also found that rates for 15-year
mortgages, a popular option for refinancing, averaged 6.60 percent
this week, the lowest level since February and down from 6.65
percent last week.
</P>
<P>
On one-year adjustable rate mortgages, lenders were asking an
average initial rate of 5.60 percent, also the lowest since
February and down from 5.66 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
The low mortgage rates have been a boon to the housing industry
this year. Sales of new single-family homes climbed to an annual
rate of 890,000 units in May, the highest level since the
government began tracking them in 1963. May also was the ninth
consecutive month that sales have been at or above the 800,000
mark, the longest such streak in 21 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: U.S Troops Continue to Stay in S.Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said on Thursday that the United States would continue to
deploy its 37,000 combat troops in the Korean Peninsula even if
the two Koreas were to be unified in the future.
</P>
<P>
"We think that should continue. And that should continue even
if there is... a unification of the two Koreas," he said at a
joint news conference with his visiting South Korean counterpart
Cheon Yong-Taek.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said South Korean President Kim Dae-jung also supported
a continued U.S. presence even after any merger of South Korea
with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
U.S. troops have been deployed in South Korea since the
1950-1953 Korean War, in which the United States was forced to
reach a truce agreement in 1953 after its defeat by DPRK and
Chinese forces.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the U.S. troops were forward-deployed in various
parts of the globe "at the request and with the consent of the
host government."
</P>
<P>
"The host (South Korean) government in this particular case
believes it's in their interest and our interest to have our
combat forces there working together and sharing responsibility
for the security of South Korea," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also argued for the necessity of deploying more than U.S.
40,000 troops in Japan, saying any pullout would create a
dangerous "vacuum" that might "be filled in a way that would not
enhance stability but detract from it."
</P>
<P>
He said Japan in current circumstances "would want us even
more, rather than less, in terms of maintaining stability in a
region that could be unstable without our presence."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Enact Code for Investment Promotion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The draft bill for investment
promotion will be tabled before the Rwandan parliament for
enactment before the end of this month, sources in the Ministry
of Finance said.
</P>
<P>
According to John Milenge, Special Assistant to the minister
of finance, the draft bill has been approved by the cabinet
meeting on July 3 with necessary package of incentives to attract
investors as well as the proposal of creating an autonomous
investment promotion agency to facilitate the investors to
acquire necessary requisites for investing in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Milenge said that there is a task force in the Ministry of
Finance which has been assisting foreign and local investors who
want to start their operations in Rwanda pending the
establishment of the agency and legislation on the Investment
Promotion Code, the Rwanda News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 World Bank report on Rwanda revealed that "the
investment rate in Rwanda has been around 11 percent of the
national gross domestic product (GDP) which appeared to be less
than what is required for rapid growth."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a four-hour workshop has been organized in the
capital Kigali by the Ministry of Commerce. The workshop focused
its discussions on information exchange and sensitization of
local businessmen about the working of the Private Sector Support
Fund (PSSF).
</P>
<P>
With a 2.5 million U.S.Dollar credit given by the World Bank,
the PSSF has been operational in Rwanda for the last six months.
It was funded through the International Development Association's
12 million Dollar funded project known as "private sector support
project" agreed upon by the government of Rwanda and the World
Bank three years ago.
</P>
<P>
The project is made up of three components: PSSF (2.5 million
Dollars), IDA creditline for local private Investors (7 million
Dollars) and private sector institutional development Unit (2.5
million Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
