<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Criticizes Nicaragua Proposal on Taiwan's Status (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government expressed
strong indignation today over a proposal by Nicaragua and a number
of other countries calling for discussion of Taiwan's
"representation" in the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Tang Guoqiang said that
Nicaragua and a number of other countries sent a letter to the
U.N. secretary general on July 8 once again asking for a
discussion of Taiwan's "representation" in the U.N., which is an
open attempt to create "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
Tang called this a serious matter and an attempt to trample on
the U.N. Charter and interference in China's internal affairs and
pointed out that the United Nations is an international
organization composed of sovereign states and only sovereign
states can be its member states and that there is only one China,
according to Resolution No.2758.
</P>
<P>
The resolution settled the issue of Chinese representation in
the U.N. in a fair and comprehensively way, and stopped the
conspiracy to create "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan,"
which the Chinese oppose as interference in China's internal
affairs, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government of the People's Republic of China is the sole
legal representative of the entire Chinese people, he said, adding
that Taiwan is internationally recognized as being a part of China
and that it therefore has no qualification to join the U.N. in any
form.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Criticizes Nicaragua Proposal on Taiwan's Status (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The spokesman also reviewed the 26th U.N. general assembly in
1971, when the People's Republic of China restored all its
legitimate rights in the U.N. under U.N. Resolution 2758.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, Tang said, all committees of the UN General
Assembly have refused to put the "Taiwan issue" on their agenda,
while the Taiwan authorities, going against history, have got a
small number of countries to keep making the proposal.
</P>
<P>
This stubborn attempt to separate the motherland will meet with
firm opposition from all Chinese, including those in Taiwan, he
said. Nicaragua and a small number of other countries, in open
defiance of the will of U.N. member nations, forget what is right
at the sight of profit given by the Taiwan authorities and
interfere in China's affairs, the spokesman said, adding that
their action will end in failure.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government's basic policy for the Taiwan issue is
"peaceful reunification and 'one country, two systems'," which was
first tried in Hong Kong July 1, 1997, and has had great success,
he said, and it will be applied again when China resumes
sovereignty over Macao in 1999.
</P>
<P>
China firmly believes that the Taiwan issue will be properly
solved eventually in accordance with the same policy, he said, and
that national reunification is the basic guarantee of Taiwan
people's interests, and they can in this way share the
motherland's dignity and honor in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
