<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Announces Collapse of Salmon Talks With Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government announced
Friday that differences over conservation caused the breakdown in
negotiations on salmon between the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
However, the State Department said in an announcement that the
two sides have agreed that their fisheries managers would work
closely together during the fishing season to ensure conservation
of the stocks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two sides agreed to close the disputed boundary
waters of the Dixon Entrance to salmon fishing this summer as a
result of Canada's concerns about the conservation of coho stocks,
the department said.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. remains committed to the process of negotiating a
resolution to the U.S.-Canadian differences under the Pacific
salmon treaty for the long term," the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement expressed regret that after making substantial
progress and reaching some agreements the talks did not produce a
comprehensive accord on Pacific salmon fisheries for the summer
fishing season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
