<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian PM Says Sino-Indian Border Peaceful, But </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee conceded Friday there is peace, tranquillity and
stability along the Sino-Indian border.
</P>
<P>
During a debate on the work of the External Affairs Ministry in
the Rajya Sabha, the Upper House of Indian Parliament, Vajpayee
said New Delhi was keen to resolve the border dispute with China
by giving a further impetus to the dialogue between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
On relations with Pakistan, the Indian prime minister said
India and Pakistan should sign an agreement on no first use of
nuclear weapons and jointly impress upon nuclear powers the need
for a complete and time-bound elimination of nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
"We should reach an agreement on no first use of nuclear
weapons and together appeal to the nuclear power countries to have
a time-bound program to eliminate stockpiles of nuclear weapons,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said his country was willing to resume dialogue with
Pakistan but there could be no third party mediation on Kashmir,
saying "we would like to solve problems ourselves, bilaterally".
</P>
<P>
Stating that India wanted friendly and normal relations with
Pakistan, Vajpayee expressed his hope that his scheduled meeting
with Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on the sidelines of the
Colombo summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) later this month would help start the stalled
dialogue between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee reiterated that India would not sign the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) under what he called the dictates of
nuclear powers and asserted that New Delhi would not succumb to
any external pressure to stall its nuclear weaponization and
missile programs.
</P>
<P>
The CTBT in its present form is not acceptable, he said, adding
that India has already announced a moratorium on further tests and
this should be considered by the five nuclear powers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
