<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Official Denies U.S. Pressure Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Cabinet Secretary Denny
Naveh denied Friday that the United States is pressuring Israel
to reach an agreement with the Palestinians over the further
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Naveh stressed that the
U.S. was not pressing Israel to accept its peace initiative
calling for a 13 percent handover of the West Bank to the
Palestinians in the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Naveh noted that if the Palestinians fulfilled their
commitments to fighting terrorism, an agreement could be signed in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
He said that Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was making a
major effort to close the gaps with the Palestinians and the
international community would realize this eventually.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been stalled for 16
months mainly due to the dispute over the extent of the next
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority has formally accepted the
U.S. initiative, but the Israeli government has rejected it citing
that the proposed scope would endanger the security interests of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials have repeatedly warned that the stalemate
in the peace process could lead to the eruption of violence in
the region.
</P>
<P>
As the leading mediator in the peace process, the U.S. has been
trying to persuade Israel to accept its plan so to break the
prolonged deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Naveh made the remarks as U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright was holding talks with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa and Jordanian Foreign Minister Jawad Anani in Washington to
discuss ways of reviving the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries have become increasingly critical of Washington
for its failure to rein in the Israeli government. Reports from
Washington said that Albright once again pressed Netanyahu to
reach an accord with the Palestinians on the redeployment.
</P>
</TEXT>
