<HEADLINE> France, Germany Back Russian Economic Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and
French President Jacques Chirac on Friday backed the Russian
governments anti-crisis program to stabilize the economy.
</P>
<P>
Their support came after Russian President Boris Yeltsin
discussed his government's plans over the telephone with Western
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Kohl and Chirac expressed their support for Moscow's program to
bring down interest rates and boost tax collection in a bid to
drag Russia out of the economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The talks also touched on the situation in the world financial
market, an official with Yeltsin's press service was quoted by
Interfax news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said the government program, which is under debate in
the upper and lower houses of the Russian parliament, was also
discussed in talks between Russia and the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Kohl and Chirac welcomed the talks, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Chubais, Yeltsin's chief negotiator to international
financial institutions, said that decision on a package of 10 to
15 billion U.S. dollars in Western loans could be reached next
week.
</P>
<P>
Interfax said Yeltsin would also telephone U.S. President Bill
Clinton and IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus later Friday.
</P>
<P>
More telephone conversations with British Prime Minister Tony
Blair, Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and leaders of
other countries in the Group of Seven industrialized nations (G7)
were also planned, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
