<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Launches Six Satellites After Repeated Delays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Friday successfully
launched a Zenit-2 rocket booster, putting into orbit six
satellites for Australia, Chile, Germany, Israel, Russia and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The launch, conducted by the Russian Strategic Rocket Troop
from the Baikonur cosmodrome in Kazakhstan, was put off three
times in June due to malfunctions first in the rocket and later in
the automatic system which controls the launch.
</P>
<P>
The lift-off Friday was again postponed by 42 minutes, but the
Russian Space Agency gave no reason for the delay, the Itar-Tass
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Resurs-O will be engaged in ecological monitoring,
natural resources investigation and meteorology, the agency
reported, quoting Yuri Trifonov, deputy managing director of the
All-Russian Research Institute of Electrical Mechanics, where the
spacecraft was manufactured.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time Australia and Thailand uses Russian
services to put into orbit their satellites.
</P>
<P>
Previous launches in 1995 by Russia of a Chilean satellite and
an Israeli one failed.
</P>
<P>
The two-stage Zenit rockets are manufactured by the Ukrainian
Yuzhmash factory. The ecologically clean booster is believed to be
among the best medium-class rockets.
</P>
<P>
However, seven out of 28 launches of this rocket failed in the
past, Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
The Russians are now equipping the Zenit with a third stage and
plan to use the new version rockets in launches from the floating
cosmodrome Sea Start next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
