<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Like Chretien, But Want Him to Go: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien enjoys a remarkably strong approval rating, but a clear
majority of Canadians want him to retire before the next election,
according to a poll published Friday.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-eight percent of respondents said Chretien, who has been
in office for the last five years, should step aside after 2000 so
someone else can lead the country. Only 38 percent think he should
stay.
</P>
<P>
The findings come at a time when many loyalists are putting out
the word that Chretien might consider going for a third term in
2001 or 2002. He himself has been coy on the question, according
to the Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Interestingly, the survey found that Canadians are content,
even pleased, with their prime minister's performance in office
but still think his time should be winding down.
</P>
<P>
Chretien now enjoys a 65 percent approval rating from
Canadians, well above that accorded him during last year's general
election.
</P>
<P>
Respondents give him high marks on such matters as the
day-to-day running of the government, keeping Canada together,
management of the economy, providing leadership that is right for
the times and presiding over an honest and trustworthy government.
</P>
<P>
The poll suggests that if an election were held today, Chretien
will win a stronger majority than he secured in the general
election a year ago. His party has the backing of 49 percent of
Canadians, well above the 38 percent last June.
</P>
<P>
The Globe and Mail/Angus Reid poll, which was conducted in late
June, is considered accurate to within plus or minus 2.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
