<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Kill 234 in Sichuan And Zhejiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A total of 234 people have been
reported dead as a result of serious flooding in east China's
Zhejiang Province and southwestern province of Sichuan, the
Ministry of Civil Affairs said here today.
</P>
<P>
Since June, 27 cities and 158 counties in the two provinces,
which have a combined population of 15 million, have been flooded
as a result of the unusually heavy rains. Floodwaters have
destroyed 100,000 houses and left more than 90,000 people homeless.
</P>
<P>
The flooding also affected more than a million hectares of
cropland and caused serious damages to local infrastructure like
irrigation facilities, communications, power, and highways, and
direct losses of 4.6 billion yuan (about 500 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Ministry says that the provincial capital Chengdu, the iron
and steel center Panzhihua, and Guangyuan, Yibin, Meizhou and
Liangshan were the areas most seriously hit in Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
In Zhejiang, the flooding mainly hit the central and southern
regions, and the new Jinhua-Wenzhou railway was close for a while.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials say that the Sichuan and Zhejiang
governments have been involved in the fight against the flooding
and have allocated 30 million yuan and over 20 million yuan
respectively for flood relief.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of June, serious flooding has been reported
in many parts of China, mostly south of the Yangtze River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
