<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Monetary Union Roadshow in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A European Monetary Union (EMU)
Roadshow was held here at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition
Center here Friday afternoon, to brief local industrialists and
businessmen on the role of the euro and its effect on the economy
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Jurgen Pfister, head of the Economics Department of the
Commerzbank, Germany, said the euro will promote competition and
lead to higher efficiency in the production and distribution of
goods and services and also to more concentration or large units.
</P>
<P>
Above all, he said European monetary integration is not a plot
against anybody. An economic strengthening of Western Europe will
also benefit Asia and North America.
</P>
<P>
He said a single currency will reduce transaction and hedging
costs and exchange-rate uncertainty will disappear. It will also
further lower the barriers to market entry within the European
Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
Pfister said Asia is important for Europe just as Europe is
important for Asia. If intra-EU trade is excluded, one quarter of
the EU's external trade is conducted with Asia. Until recently,
deliveries to Asia have been the most dynamic element in Western
Europe's export growth.
</P>
<P>
"I am fairly confident that in a few years time Asia will
regain its prominent role in the world economy," he added.
</P>
<P>
During the EMU Roadshow, Jean-Claude Trichet, governor of the
Bank of France and future president of the European Central Bank,
and Professor Antonio Borges, dean of the European Institute of
Business Administration and former governor of the Central Bank of
Portugal, also delivered speeches.
</P>
<P>
The event was sponsored by the Hong Kong General Chamber of
Commerce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
