<HEADLINE> Canada to Take Feud with Brazil to WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The talks between Brazil and Canada
to avert a showdown over aerospace sales have broken down
completely, "The Globe and Mail" newspaper reported friday.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian federal government will file a challenge against
Brazil friday at the World Trade Organization, requesting a
binding dispute panel to settle the long and bitter dispute
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Trade officials from Brazil and Canada have gone through two
months of intense meetings in an attempt to implement a specially
commissioned report suggesting solutions to the aerospace dispute,
which has plagued commercial relations between the two countries
for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
But the talks have led nowhere, a Canadian senior government
source said thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ottawa has accused Brazil of unfairly subsidizing aerospace
giant Embraer(Empresa Brasileira de Aeronautica SA) through an
export subsidy that offers buyers of Brazilian aircraft
below-market interest rates. The subsidy program, called Proex,
reduces the price of each plane by about 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Proex undercuts Canadian aerospace sales unfairly in a highly
competitive international market, the government source argued,
and it breaks WTO rules on export subsidies.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian aerospace sector employs about 60,000 people at
about 400 companies.
</P>
<P>
But Brazil has also accused Canada of breaking rules by
discreetly subsidizing Montreal-based Bombardier Inc., Canada's
biggest aerospace company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
