<HEADLINE> Blair Urges for Calm in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
appealed for calm in Northern Ireland, saying attacking police was
not tolerated and upholding the rule of law was "paramount."
</P>
<P>
"People can have their different points of view, they can
express them and they can make their protests. I understand
there are strongly held views on either side," Blair said in a
brief interview with BBC TV at his Downing Street residence.
</P>
<P>
"But the rule of law is paramount. That is what we have to
enforce without fear or favour and we cannot allow our police
and our security forces to be attacked by anybody," he added.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after five Northern Ireland police officers
were seriously injured in increasingly violent clashes on Friday
with Protestants angered at a ban on their annual march through a
flashpoint Catholic area.
</P>
<P>
Blair said he was still trying to get an agreement over a
disputed Protestant march in Portadown and would not allow the
peace process to be "hijacked by extremists from any side."
</P>
<P>
"I will carry on talking to whoever I can and as many people
as I can," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to a Downing Street spokesman, Blair spoke by
telephone on Friday morning to Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams and
planned to talk later to Irish prime minister Bertie Ahern and
Northern Ireland's first minister-designate David Trimble, leader
of the Protestant Ulster Unionist Party, in a bid to seek a way out
of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, troops are strengthening barricades at Drumcree
after Orangemen breached part of their defenses in clashes
overnight.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Belfast said troops have laid more barbed wire and
put in scaffolding and concrete blocks to stop the marchers from
walking down the controversial route. 
</P>
</TEXT>
