<HEADLINE> Pakistan Wins SAARC Youth Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Dr. Najmul Hasbaub Shah of
Pakistan has won the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) Youth Award-1998 under the theme, "New
Inventions and Discoveries", according to a Foreign Ministry press
release Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
The award carries a gold medal, a cash prize of 500 U.S.
dollars, and a citation in English.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Shah has been awarded the honor for his discovery regarding
the virulence of haemorrhagic septicemia (HS) causing bacteria of
cattle and buffalo, the release said.
</P>
<P>
This discovery describes the production of vacuolating
cytotoxic activity by pasteurella multocida serotype B and E,
affecting macrophages, the release noted.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old Shah is a veterinary doctor currently serving
at the Center of Animal Biotechnology of the Veterinary Research
Institute in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC Youth Awards Scheme was initiated last year aimed at
encouraging the young talent in the member states of SAARC to
excel in different fields.
</P>
<P>
SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Pakistan,
Nepal and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The award will be presented to the recipient at the forthcoming
session of the SAARC Council of Ministers in Colombo on July
27-28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
