<HEADLINE> Russian Upper House Critical of Government Anti-Crisis Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Federation Council, or
upper house of parliament, on Friday criticized the government's
stabilization program as insufficient to overcome the economic and
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution passed Friday after hearing Prime Minister
Sergei Kiriyenko's report on the program, the lawmakers said
measures proposed by the cabinet were "obviously insufficient" to
tackle the causes of the debt and budget crisis, depression and
shrinking investment activity in the real sector.
</P>
<P>
"The program does not contain measures to revive industrial
production, raise investment activity, increase the
competitiveness of national industrial output, strengthen currency
controls, ensure the ruble's stability or provide social
protection for the population," the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The document was approved by a 97 to four vote with two
abstentions, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Despite the overall tone of criticism, Kiriyenko's dialogue
with the senators appeared to have achieved some positive results.
</P>
<P>
Yegor Stroyev, chairman of the Federation Council, said the
upper house and the cabinet had reached mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time, the Federation Council and the government
were speaking the same language," Stroyev said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian Deputy Prime Minister Viktor Khristenko
reiterated that there was no real threat of ruble devaluation.
</P>
<P>
"The whole government stabilization program is designed to
prevent devaluation," Khristenko told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
