<HEADLINE> S.Korea to Crackdown on Illegal Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government warned
Friday that it will take tough action against any illegal strikes
and protest rallies.
</P>
<P>
"The government will sternly deal with any illegal labor strikes in
accordance with the law," Acting Prime Minister Kim Jong-pil said.
</P>
<P>
Kim made the remarks before starting his trip to France and
Poland.
</P>
<P>
Kim's warning came after the Federation of Korean Trade Unions
and the Korean Confederation of Trade threatened to stage huge
rallies Saturday and general strikes next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of unions are threatening strikes in
protest against government-led corporate and financial
restructuring and the mass layoffs as the country is racked by the
Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The government needs to be strict in dealing with the
organizers of illegal strikes and maintaining social order," Kim
told a cabinet meeting attended by the ministers of justice,
labor, government administration and local autonomy, finance and
economy, and the police chief.
</P>
<P>
The government feared that labor unrest would obstruct its
efforts to overcome the economic crisis and push through reforms,
said a government spokesman Friday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is carrying out painful corporate and financial
restructuring under an agreement signed last December with the
International Monetary Fund for a rescue loan of 57 billion U.S.
dollars after it was hit by a financial crisis caused by corporate
failures and bad loans by financial institutions late last year.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, South Korea promised to carry out reforms
including financial reforms and the legalization of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
The number of jobless South Koreans, which stood at 1.5 million
in May, is expected to shoot up in the coming months as a result
of corporate and financial restructuring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
