<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism on the Rise in E.U. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's tourism
industry is enjoying a healthy growth rate, netting the 15 member
states an eight billion ECU (8.82 billion U.S. dollar) surplus
last year.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by Eurostat on Friday revealed EU
holidaymakers spent 135 billion ECUs (148 billion dollars) outside
the community while non-EU residents brought in 143 billion ECUs
(157 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Total nights spent in registered tourist accommodation in the
EU rose by 1.5 percent last year, said the Luxembourg-based
statistical office.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, nights spent in the 11-nation euro currency zone
were up 0.9 percent in that period, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The euro countries are Belgium, Germany, Spain, France, Italy,
Ireland, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and
Finland.
</P>
<P>
Non-EU residents were the major contributers to the rise, with
an increase of 3.1 percent in accomodation nights, compared with a
mere 0.4 percent rise by EU residents.
</P>
<P>
Greece, France and Finland posted a rise of more than 10
percent in nights spent by non-residents while Spain registered a
12.2 percent increase in nights spent by residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
