<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Friday:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. Senate gave final approval to legislation
overhauling the Internal Revenue Service, voting 96-2 to impose
the most sweeping shake-up in decades on the tax-collection
agency's management and culture. President Bill Clinton said he
would sign the bill into law.
</P>
<P>
-- The United States set out new conditions for taking part in
an international criminal court, calling for sharp limits on its
scope and authority. The United States said it could agree to the
court only if automatic jurisdiction were limited to genocide and
not crimes against humanity or war crimes like rape and torture.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- With the collapse of a comprehensive tobacco bill, the
nation's largest tobacco companies have been trying to negotiate a
multibillion-dollar settlement of the dozens of state lawsuits
pending against the industry.
</P>
<P>
-- The Senate vote 98 to 0 Thursday to exempt farm credit
programs from the economic sanctions imposed on India and Pakistan
following their nuclear weapons tests in May. But only after the
bill was stripped of provisions that would have authorized
President Clinton to waive the other sanctions as well.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Indonesia's president urged the ruling Golker party to break
with its authoritarian past, and said the economic crisis shows no
sign of abating. As many as half of the nation's 200 million
people face food shortages by year's end.
</P>
<P>
-- Tests of a new missile defense were postponed by the
Pentagon after the first five tests of the Theater High Altitude
Area Defense System failed. The military is taking steps to revamp
the program and punish lockheed. 
</P>
