<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Declares War Against Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
Friday mobilized the government and all sectors of society in an
all-out war against poverty.
</P>
<P>
Keynoting the general assembly of the Bishops-Businessmen
Conference, Estrada called on the clergy and business to help him
convince rich and poor Filipinos alike that "they have an equal
stake in the success of their country."
</P>
<P>
He said the economy needs peace and stability to flourish and
this conducive atmosphere can only be achieved if the wealth of
the land is enjoyed by every Filipino.
</P>
<P>
He bewailed that poverty has become so prevalent that the poor
and their plight are "simply part of the landscape" and a "daily
reality to which we have become accustomed."
</P>
<P>
Estrada also reminded businessmen it is the poor's hard-earned
money that sustains their fortune which, he said, should serve as
an impetus for them to help improve the living standard and
purchasing power of the masses.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who won the May 11 presidential polls on a populist
pro-poor platform, has vowed to reduce the country's poverty
incidence to 20 percent from the present 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said earlier that his administration would try to ease
poverty in the country with a population of 70 million by giving
priority to developing its backward agriculture sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
