<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal's GDP Grows by 1.9 Percent: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product (GDP)
of Nepal is expected to grow by only 1.9 percent in the 1997/98
fiscal year which ends in mid-July, the lowest in 22 years, said
the Economic Survey presented by the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the GDP grew by four percent in the last
fiscal year, and the decrease is attributed to the decline in the
growth rates of agriculture and non-agriculture sectors.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture, which contributes 40 percent to the GDP and
employs more than 80 percent of the economically active population
of the country, is estimated to grow by only 1.1 percent,
reflecting a fall of three percentage points over last year, noted
the report covering the first nine months of the current fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
Because of inadequate irrigation facilities, the agriculture
sector is still dependent on monsoon. And in the current fiscal
year, production of food crops is estimated to decline by one
percent to 6.361 million metric tons compared with last year, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The non-agriculture sectors as a whole are expected to grow by
3.1 percent, down from last year's 3.8 percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the volume of savings, as a proportion of
total production, is declining, and the current account deficit of
the external sector is increasing.
</P>
<P>
Especially, as there was no improvement in revenue mobilization
as anticipated, the gap between sources and utilization of
resources became wider, resulting in added loan liabilities, the
report added.
</P>
<P>
"Budget deficit is increasing every year," it warned. "It leads
to a situation in which the scope of national saving deteriorates,
the current account deficit of the balance of payments increases
further, the problem of loan service becomes worse and financial
resources for the private sector become scarce."
</P>
<P>
"Besides, it creates distortions like the erosion in people's
purchasing power due to the decline in internal and external value
of the currency, capital flight and distraction of foreign
investment," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate in the fields of electricity, gas, water and
construction has been negative whereas the growth rate of industry
and mining has come down, the report said.
</P>
<P>
During the first nine months of the current fiscal year, total
foreign trade recorded a decrease of 0.3 percent as compared with
the same period of last year, but the total trade deficit during
the review period has gone down by 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
And the situation of increasing unemployment and
quasi-employment remains the main problem of the nation, it said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that higher growth rate, in comparison with the
previous year, could be attained only in the sectors of community
and social services and financial and housing.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that attributes of macroeconomic stability
have prevailed in the economy as the price increase has been
controlled, interest rate has been reduced somewhat and
considerable surplus has been maintained in the balance of
payments.
</P>
<P>
"On this basis, it seems that a favorable environment has been
created for the increase in production in the country in future
through the promotion of investment," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
