<HEADLINE> Expelled Russian Diplomat Proclaims Innocence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Expelled Russian diplomat, Oleg
N. Abramkin, declared innocence before leaving for home Friday
afternoon after he was declared persona non grata by South Korea
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I have collected information on South Korea's domestic
politics and foreign affairs during the four years of my stay
here, but I did not collect information on security or anything I
am ashamed of doing," Abramkin said before departure at Seoul
Kimpo International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Abramkin, a councelor of the Russian Embassy to Seoul, said he
is worried that relations between South Korea may worsen due to
the diplomatic conflict.
</P>
<P>
However, the Russian diplomat hoped that he would be the last
person to be sacrificed over such an incident.
</P>
<P>
"I also hope that my government will take no additional measure and
the bilateral relations will be recovered soon," he said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea Wednesday ordered Abramkin to leave the nation within
72 hours in retaliation against Russia's expulsion of Cho Sung-woo, a
councelor of the South Korean Embassy in Moscow, on espionage charges
last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Cho was caught red-handed last Friday when he was giving money to
Valentin Moiseyev, deputy director general for Asian-Pacific affairs
of the Russian Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Russia accused Cho of bribing Moiseyev to secure classified
information, which the South Korean government denied.
</P>
<P>
This morning, Valery Suhinin, a minister-counsellor of the Russian
Embassy here complained about the South Korean government's decision
to expel the Russian councelor in retaliation, saying that Cho's case
is different from Abramkin's in nature.
</P>
<P>
Thursday, Russian Foreign Ministry stated that it is seriously
mulling over taking some additional actions against South Korea in
response to the latter's deportation of Abramkin.
</P>
<P>
The ministry added that South Korea has made the bilateral
relations intense and it is now up to Russia to make response.
</P>
</TEXT>
