<HEADLINE> Kuwait Urged to Cancel Sale of Iraqi Oil Tankers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has asked the U.N. chief to
immediately intervene with Kuwaiti authorities to cancel the sale
of five Iraqi oil tankers seized since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency reported Friday that in a letter to
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Thursday, Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf said the Kuwaiti move is "illegal and
violating international law."
</P>
<P>
Iraq had received reports Kuwaiti authorities had sold five
Iraqi oil tankers, seized since 1991 when Iraqi occupying troops
were driven out of Kuwait by the coalition forces, to other
parties as junk at 16.5 million dollars, al-Sahhaf said.
</P>
<P>
He said four of the five oil tankers were in good condition and
one was damaged, and they were owned by Iraq and registered in
international navigation records under the name of "Iraqi Oil
Tankers Company."
</P>
<P>
"Any such action by the Kuwaiti authorities will be illegal and
have no legal grounds," he added.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf said Iraqi government demands that Kuwaiti
authorities return these oil tankers to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq reserves legal right to compensations for any damage
done by Kuwaiti authorities to its property, and to prosecute the
purchasers and take legal action against them in any state of the
world," he warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
