<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World War II Japanese Military Atlas Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A Japanese military atlas of
China used in World War II has been found here, providing more
evidence of Japan's aggression against China during the war.
</P>
<P>
The atlas, called "The New Pocket Atlas of Manchoukuo," was
printed by a publishing house in Tokyo in 1940, according to its
introduction.
</P>
<P>
The book, 14.5 cm long and eight cm wide, has a black cover and
can fit in the hand.
</P>
<P>
The atlas includes eight maps depicting the locations of 18
provinces including Jilin and Binjiang in the so-called
"Manchoukuo" region, now the northeast China area.
</P>
<P>
The atlas was found by Jin Deyuan, a retired teacher from
Changchun City No. 92 Secondary School. It was discovered among the
possessions of his late father-in-law.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, eight Japanese military atlas used during
World War II have been found in Dongning County, Heilongjiang
Province, providing more evidence of Japan's aggression against China
during that period.
</P>
<P>
Japanese aggressors occupied northeast China in 1931 and set up
the puppet "Manchoukuo" regime in 1934. Northeast China was
controlled by the Japanese aggressors until they surrendered in
1945. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
