<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Sharply Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket closed
the week sharply lower, halting 10 straight days of higher
finishes.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index ended 41 points, or 1.47 percent,
lower at 2747.9, off a high of 2788.9 and a low of 2743.6.
</P>
<P>
The market opened weaker, undermined by a fall on international
shares and commodity markets. Overnight the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 85 points to 9,089.
</P>
<P>
Lucinda Chan, an expert from Macquarie Equities, said the fall
on the U.S. market and the Asian markets' poor performances led to
the local sell-off.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index closed down 67.7 points at 4830.9 and
the All Resources Index fell 20 points to 1066.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 286 million shares valued at 619.9
million U.S. dollars, with falls outnumbering rises by 645 to 344.
</P>
<P>
At the close in Sydney the Australian dollar was buying 61.53
U.S. cents from Thursday's close of 62.09 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, the sub index slid 81.4 points to
6029.3.
</P>
<P>
Among the banks, the Commonwealth Bank of Australia slipped 28
cents to 19.85 Australian dollars. The bank earlier announced that
it had formed a joint venture with retailing group Woolworths and
predicted that the deal would be profitable in the first year.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank fell 15 cents to 22.45 Australian
dollars, Westpac Banking Corp. lost 19 cents to 10.48 Australian
dollars and ANZ Banking Group dropped 20 cents to 11.53 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, Australia's leading company BHP was
down 15 cents at 14.21 Australian dollars. Global mining giant Rio
Tinto was down 55 cents, or 2.86 percent, at 18.65 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The spot price for Sydney gold bullion was 290.85 U.S. dollars
an ounce, compared with Thursday's close of 292.75 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was down 43 points, or 3.85 percent, at 1075.2.
