<HEADLINE> Australia Unveils Tax Break Plan for TCF Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government Friday
announced a 463 million U.S. dollar package to encourage the
nation's textile, clothing and footwear (TCF) industry to increase
investment and stem job losses amid growing competition from
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The five-year package announced by Australian Federal Industry
Minister John Moore at a clothing factory in Melbourne Friday is
to take effect from July 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The package, known as "TCF Strategic Investment Program", will
provide tax breaks for TCF businesses spending money on equipment,
research and development.
</P>
<P>
Tens of millions of dollars would also be pumped into new
technologies, training, export expansion, and encouraging the use
of Australian textiles by overseas manufacturers, Moore said.
</P>
<P>
The plan comes on top of a government announcement last
September to freeze tariffs in the industry, which employs 100,000
Australians, at year 2000 levels until 2005.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, tariffs are to be reduced to 15 percent for
textiles and footwear and 25 percent for clothing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
