<HEADLINE> China to Follow Family Planning Policy into Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- China will continue its family
planning policy in the next 50 years to maintain its
population at about 1.6 billion in the middle 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Weiqing, director of the State Family Planning
Commission, made the statement today at a meeting in Beijing
marking World Population Day on July 11.
</P>
<P>
Based on a forecast that the world population will reach six
billion in 1999, the United Nations has chosen "approaching six
billion" as the theme of this year's World Population Day.
</P>
<P>
"As the most populous country in the world, China is deeply
concerned with the pressure brought by rapid population growth,
and is also responsible for stablizing world population growth and
maintaining sustainable global development," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China should stick to the basic state policies of
family planning and environmental protection, and coordinate
population growth with economic development and environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
China plans to have its population under 1.3 billion by the end
of this century, and under 1.4 billion by 2010, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the two decades of family planning in China
have resulted in 300 million fewer people, and the population
growth rate has dropped from 2.6 percent in the late 1970s to 1.06
percent.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with population control, China has been trying to
reduce the incidence of defects in newborn babies and provide
better reproductive health care for women of child-bearing
age, he said.
</P>
<P>
China's State Family Planning Commission, along with the
Representative Office of the United Nations Population Fund in
China and relevant Chinese departments, will hold an event from
July 10 to July 19 in Beijing to mark the World Population Day.
</P>
<P>
Sponsors of the event will discuss China's achievements in
population control and provide information and services related to
reproductive health care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh River Heavily Polluted: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The water in the Buriganga River
flowing through this South Asian nation's capital city of Dhaka
has been seriously polluted depleting almost all kinds of fish,
according to a survey available here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We have not seen a single fishing boat from Mirpur (10
kilometers north of Dhaka) to Pagla point (about 15 kilometers
southeast of here) because of non-availability of fish," said the
survey, conducted by the Surface Water Modeling Center (SWMC)
under the Water Resources Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Dissolved oxygen (DO) levels within the 17 kilometer reach of
the river stretching from Savar to Narayanganj, on the northwest
and southeast outskirts of the capital respectively, were found to
be far below the acceptable level of four milligrams per liter --
the threshold level for survival of aquatic life including fish,
the survey said.
</P>
<P>
The SWMC monitored the DO level at more than 11 points in 1995,
and took samples of water from the river for laboratory tests.
</P>
<P>
A preliminary review of the data showed that the DO level
within the 17 kilometer reach of the river was at some points as
low as 0.1 milligram per liter.
</P>
<P>
Seeped-in residue of chemical fertilizers and pesticides, along
with discharge of human excreta and wastes from industries on the
banks, were the main reasons behind the fall of DO levels, which
caused the depletion of fish in the river, SWMC experts said.
</P>
<P>
There were traces of many hazardous chemicals in the river
water even in the upstream, they pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Environmental experts warned that the pollution might turn the
river into a dead river if pragmatic steps were not taken
immediately. Only efficient management practices, with balance
between the environment and development, can save the river, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Controlling and managing the river resources of the country was
very important and a balance should achieved between the sometimes
conflicting requirements of food production, irrigation and
fisheries, which required management tools capable of integrating
all relevant processes, they said.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the SWMC said that final results of the tests and
their analysis which were expected to be available soon would help
assess the environmental impact, and the planning and
implementation of river restoration schemes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
