<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Cereal Output Expected at 1,911 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Food and Agriculture Organization
(FAO) now forecasts world cereal production this year at 1,911
million tons compared to 1,909 million tons of last year.
</P>
<P>
Wheat output is forecast at 606 millin tons, 1.5 percent down
from 1997. Asia's output is expected to slip back somewhat from
the record harvest in 1997 but would remain well above the
average of the past few years, accordong to the latest issue of
food outlook published by FAO.
</P>
<P>
In south America the continuing El Nino is affecting
production prospects but output should be only slightly below
average and in north America, wheat output is forecast to
decrease considerably due to a significant decline in plantings
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
In the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), adverse
weather and farmers' economic problems are expected to reduce
production this year.
</P>
<P>
In Africa, improved weather conditions in the major wheat
producing areas has allowed a recovery from last year's
drought-reduced crops, while in Europe, Oceania and central
America the wheat harvests are expected to remain close to last
year's level.
</P>
<P>
For coarse grains, global output this year is expected at 925
million tons, 1.6 percent up from 1997.
</P>
<P>
FAO's forecast for global paddy output is 567 million tons
(380 million tons in milled terms), only four million tons less
than 1997. However, this forecast is still very tentative as the
bulk of the 1998 rice crop is yet to be planted in Asia pending
the arrival of the monsoon rains.
</P>
<P>
In northern Africa, the aggregate output is preliminarily
forcast at 13.7 million tons, some 40 percent higher than last
year's drought-affected crops.
</P>
<P>
Aggregate output of coarse grains of this year in the
sub-Sahara region is forecast at some 11.2 million tons, about 21
percent higher than last year.
</P>
<P>
In southern Africa, a below average output of some 15.5
million tons is preliminarily estimated compared with 17 million
tons of last year.
</P>
<P>
World cereal trade in 1998/99 (July/June) could decrease to
201 million tons, nearly four million tons, or two percent below
1997/98.
</P>
<P>
Global wheat trade in 1998/99 is likely to fall to 90 million
tons, five million tons below that of 1997/98 and the lowest
level since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
World coarse grain trade in 1998/99 points to an expansion of
over three million tons, bringing the total to 91 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In Africa, maize imports will increase sharply in 1898/99.
Most of the expected increase in imports would be in southern
Africa, where crop reductions associated with El Nino in some
countries are expected to lift import requirements, particularly
in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is expected to return to the import market mainly to
replenish stocks while substantially large imports are also
anticipated in Lesotho and Namibia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
