He noted that the crisis is caused by the opposition National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), who, on the
one hand, refuses to hand over the four cities in central Angola,
and on the other hand is snatching back the cities from the
government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman said, UNITA has planted landmines
back to the de-mined roads, destroying bridges and attacking
unarmed citizens, rendering thousands of people homeless and
reducing them to new refugees.
</P>
<P>
According to Culolo, it is UNITA who proposed to hand over the
four cities under its control to the government by June 30. Since
there are no concrete actions so far to this end, it shows that
UNITA does not have the political will to keep its promise.
</P>
<P>
All members of the republic council have agreed that the
situation is "grim", Culolo said.
</P>
<P>
He also extended the council's deep condolences to the death
of Alioune Blondin Beye, special envoy of the United Nations to
Angola, saying it hopes the U.N. will soon appoint a new envoy so
as to put the Angola Peace Process back on course.
</P>
<P>
Angola Republic Council is the advisory body for the
president. It comprises the president, prime minister,
government ministers, chief procurator, chief justice of the
Supreme Court and heads of political parties which have seats in
the parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
