<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The German carmaker Bayerische
Motoren Werke AG (BMW) Friday dismissed news reports that it is
seeking a strategic alliance, even a possible merger, with car
manufacturer Fiat of Italy.
</P>
<P>
This week's edition of the British weekly Economist reportedly
said that executives "at the highest level" of BMW and Fiat have
met to see whether a merger between the two was possible.
</P>
<P>
Dismissing the report, a BMW spokesman said in Munich on
Friday, "That is absolutely rubbish."
</P>
<P>
Fiat has also denied the report.
</P>
<P>
Speculations about a BMW-Fiat marriage came after a series of
offensives taken by German carmakers in the global auto industry
in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
Germany's largest industrial concern Daimler-Benz AG is
currently in the process of forging a merger with the United
States' third-largest carmaker Chrysler while Volkswagen AG has
just won a battle against BMW to take over the British luxury
carmaker Rolls-Royce. 
