<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shirt-pulling, Feigning New Headaches for Referees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Shirt-pulling and simulations of
injuries by players have become new head-aches for referees in the
World Cup, a FIFA official said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
As the previously much debated tacklings from behind faded out of
picture, gaining advantage through pulling of opponents' shirt and
making deceiving dives have become popular, said Volker Roth, a member
of the Referees' Committee.
</P>
<P>
"Now they are pulling (shirts). They are making more simulations,"
Roth told a news conference. "This is dangerous for football."
</P>
<P>
Roth admitted that it was almost impossible to watch out for all
the players' actions especially when they gathered in the penalty area
during a corner kick.
</P>
<P>
He praised the linesmen's work at this World Cup, saying "they were
exceptionally good and much better than four years ago in the United
States."
</P>
<P>
Roth added the performance of the assisstant referees here even set
the standard for some European leagues.
</P>
<P>
But he ruled out a possibility of using video technology to
refereeing a soccer game.
</P>
<P>
"This would make football a different sport," he said. "If we use
video supervising in such a top-level competition here but don't
change things in the lower level, we would divide football."
</P>
<P>
He argued that players in underdeveloped areas in Asia and Africa
would have to play "another game" if they could not afford video-aided
refereeing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
