<HEADLINE> Crisis in N.Ireland Deepens as Stand-off Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The crisis in Northern Ireland
deepened on Friday as Protestants warned major trouble within days
unless a way was found to end the stand-off in Portadown.
</P>
<P>
David Jones, spokesman of the Protestant Orange Order, said
there would be a mass bid to break through security forces' lines
and end the march down the Catholic Garvaghy Road in Portadown, 50
km southwest of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
"Is (Prime Minister) Tony Blair prepared to have another Bloody
Sunday, only this time in Portadown?" Jones was quoted by BBC as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Orange Order has been banned from staging its annual march
along the traditional route through Garvaghy Road for fear of
igniting conflicts with Catholic residents in the area. But they
continued on Sunday in defiance and were halted by security forces.
</P>
<P>
Three policemen were reported to have been hurt when two bombs
were thrown by members of angry crowds in Portadown late Thursday
night. Another was injured by a flying brick.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, thousands of Orangemen have flooded into Portadown
as the Order's stand-off with police and army units entered its
sixth day.
</P>
<P>
Police estimate 20,000 to 25,000 people are in the crowds --
the biggest turnout since the Orangemen were stopped on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
As the stand-off dragged on, Northern Ireland's First Minister
David Trimble warned of "awesome" consequences facing the province
if a stand-off over a banned Protestant parade is not resolved
soon.
</P>
<P>
"Time is running out and this society faces a quite awesome
prospect if between now and the weekend we do not find a
satisfactory way out of it," he told a news conference on Thursday
after meeting Orange Order leaders in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
But Trimble said he and Deputy First Minister Seamus Mallon
were still exploring ways of averting a feared showdown on July
13, the climax of an annual series of marches commemorating
William of Orange, the Protestant king who defeated a Catholic
monarch in 1690. 
</P>
</TEXT>
