<HEADLINE> Car Prices in Gulf Region Dip to Record Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Car prices in the Gulf region
have dropped to record low levels, leaving minimal profit margins
for car dealers, a Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) report said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The price slump of new cars in Gulf countries this year is up
to an average 15-20 percent, caused by the volatile exchange rates
of major currencies, oversupply and the cut-throat competition
among manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Car dealers in Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) agreed that the yen-U.S. dollar exchange rate
recently ended in favor of customers and forced them to refer
U.S. made cars to the Japanese-manufactured.
</P>
<P>
The prospect of shipping new models by anxious manufacturers
also gave car dealers pressures, which forced them to seek a
lion's share of the market, introduce extra incentives for
customers and reap the least profit margin.
</P>
<P>
Experts predicted that current situation in the Gulf car
markets would continue for a period of time, since customers are
waiting the new models of the next century that will include
drastic changes in designs and specifications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
