<HEADLINE> Investment in Cambodia Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 10 (Xinhua) -- After several years of steady
growth, capital investment in Cambodia dropped by more than 60
percent in the first half of 1998, according to the Cambodia
Investment Board.
</P>
<P>
The board approved 65 projects worth 147.3 million U.S. dollars
during the first six months of 1998, a sharp decrease from the
same period in 1997, when more than 400 million dollars worth of
investment projects were approved.
</P>
<P>
The drop was due to worries about the country's political
stability and regional financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Keat Chhon said Monday at an ASEAN workshop
that direct foreign investment from Southeast Asia could slow down
or stop completely for at least one or two years.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the drop might be offset by investment from other
Asian countries, such as South Korea and China, as long as
Cambodia remains attractive.
</P>
<P>
Although investment has dropped significantly, investors are
still interested, provided that the election and transition period
are smooth. Investors will wait until after the new government is
formed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
