<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 43 Dar es Salaam Businessmen Netted for Violating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
has seized 43 unscrupulous businessmen in Dar es Salaam, the
capital, since the Value Added Tax (VAT) was introduced on July
1.
</P>
<P>
"The traders were netted for various offenses including
failure to register for VAT while they were qualified to do so,
charging VAT while they were not registered and overcharging
goods by imposing tax on tax," a revenue official has said.
</P>
<P>
Augustine Mukandara, a senior Tanzanian Revenue Authority
(TRA) Officer for Publicity and Taxpayer Education on VAT, said
the traders were nabbed in a nationwide crackdown on businessmen
violating the VAT Act.
</P>
<P>
The act, passed in 1997, ruled that a taxable person,
convicted after commiting an offense, is liable to a fine not
exceeding 200,000 Shillings (about 300 U.S. Dollars) or to
imprisonment for a term between two to 12 months, or suffer both
penalties.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by The Guardian on Friday, some of the
seized traders who pleaded guilty have been fined by TRA while
others who pleaded "not guilty" will be taken to court.
</P>
<P>
Mukandara said Thursday that the crackdown and education will go
on so that VAT system is properly carried out.
</P>
<P>
The new tax is applied at a standard rate of 20 percent except
for certain items that were zero-rated. Traders whose annual
turnover has reached 20 million Shillings should register for the
new tax system.
</P>
<P>
The new tax became effective in Mainland Tanzania on July 1.
Zanzibar isles plan to delay the implementation of VAT to January
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Mukandara said since July 1, another 500 traders have
registered themselves for VAT. So far, more than 9,000 traders
have registered in Mainland Tanzania, against a target of 15,000.
</P>
<P>
These days, consumer goods prices in several regions have
dropped following a period of chaos of price hikes, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
