<HEADLINE> Gigantic Hydro-Electric Power Station Built to World Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The gigantic Ertan Hydroelectric
Power Station, expected to begin operations in mid August, has
been hailed as a world-class construction masterpiece, according
to a frontpage story in today's People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
Located in the southwest China city of Panzhihua in Sichuan
Province, the facility, designed to produce 17 billion kilowatts
hours of electricity a year, cost 33 billion yuan (3.98 billion
U.S. dollars), including 930 million U.S. dollars in World Bank
loans, the largest World Bank loan ever for a single project.
</P>
<P>
According to World Bank stipulations, contractors for the
construction of the main project and the producers of major
equipment were determined through international bidding.
</P>
<P>
New bidding practices allowing foreign and Chinese companies to
compete was introduced for this project, thus enabling the Chinese
companies to learn from their overseas counterparts. The
successful bidders include companies from China, France, Italy,
Germany and Canada.
</P>
<P>
The strict implementation of more than 1,200 contracts served a
major guarantor of the success of the power station, which is
second in size only to the Three Gorges Water Conservancy project.
</P>
<P>
So far, no major disputes have occurred between the
proprietors and the contractors since construction began in
September 1991.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the gigantic power station is also a fine
example of cost-saving, as the project was completed under budget.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nanjing Weather Forecast Includes Health Alerts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Weather forecasts in Nanjing,
capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, now include
temperatures, precipitation and wind velocity, as well as heat
stroke indicators, warnings for individuals suffering from
cardiovascular diseases, and various other health alerts.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing is the first Chinese city to include health alerts in
weather forecasts.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Dingzhen, deputy director of the Nanjing Meteorological
Bureau, said health alerts are designed to prevent outbreaks of
disease and remind local residents with health problems to take
preventive measures.
</P>
<P>
The bureau also plans to introduce reports concerning
intestinal and infectious diseases, as well as the intensity of
ultraviolet rays and pollen levels.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that noted ancient people living more than 2,000
years ago fully recognized the close relationship between weather
and health.
</P>
<P>
Statistics reveal that 87 percent of heart attacks are directly
related to cold and warm wind currents, with outbreaks of asthma
related to cold or cloudy weather.
</P>
<P>
Heat strokes commonly occur on summer days when temperature
and air humidity are high and barometric pressure is low. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
