<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Philippines to Ratify Forces Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A top U.S. military official here
Friday urged the Philippine Senate to ratify the proposed Visiting
Forces Agreement which would again allow the holding of joint
military exercises between the United States and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Admiral Joseph Prueher, chief of the U.S. Armed Forces Pacific
Command, said he was encouraged by the commitment of support for
the agreement by the Estrada administration.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the agreement by the Senate "would enable us to
work together between our militaries," Prueher said after
attending a closed-door Mutual Defense Board meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. does not seek military bases in the country," he
said, reiterating that American soldiers only desire to visit
seaports in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lieutenant General Joselyn Nazareno, chief of staff
of the Philippine Armed Forces, said he supports the proposed
agreement which "is very advantageous" to the Philippine military.
</P>
<P>
It is very important for the armed forces of the Philippines to
further strengthen military ties with Washington, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Senate vetoed the extension of U.S. military
bases in Subic and Clark in 1992, forcing the U.S. forces to leave
after stationed in the Philippines for nearly a century.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada, one of the former senators who voted
against the U.S. military, has expressed support for the proposed
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The government insists that the international treaty should be
approved by the Senate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
