<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Implement Industrial Ecowatch System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Department of
Environment and Natural Resources has issued guidelines for the
implementation of the Industrial Ecowatch System across the
country, the Philippine News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the ecowatch system is an information and
public disclosure-based system which would inform the public of
the status of environmental compliance and responsiveness of
industrial and commercial firms.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, all industrial and commercial firms all over
the country will be evaluated and audited in terms of their
compliance with environmental laws, rules and regulations as well
as their responsiveness to waste water effluent and air emissions,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the firms will be rated based on five color
codes, namely black, red, blue, green and gold, to help the public
identify their compliance and responsiveness from very bad to
excellent.
</P>
<P>
The report said the system is being adopted to promote
compliance with environmental laws, rules and regulations through
public pressure; encourage pollution reduction through public
recognition and praise; create incentives for polluters to develop
internal environmental management systems; and develop foundations
for international environmental standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Landmines Raise Concerns in Somali Regions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 10 (Xinhua) -- There is a growing concern over
the threat of land mines in the central regions of Hiran and
Galgudud, where an average of two people die in the mine
explosions every week.
</P>
<P>
The Governor of Galgudud region, Yussuf Hassan Eyow, said that
along with the human casualties, dozens of the livestock
especially the camels get perished in those land mines.
</P>
<P>
The governor who spoke with the reporters in Mogadishu said
the threat is now increased by the recent rains which excavated
the land mines from under the earth where they were buried during
the height of the civil war in 1992
</P>
<P>
The peace deals which have been achieved among the different
clans living together in those regions have on the other hand
surfaced the problem of the land mines.
</P>
<P>
Most of the important roads abandoned for the hostility during
the inter-clan fighting are now the most dangerous after they
were re-opened for the use of both the traffic and herdsmen.
</P>
<P>
The mine explosion incidents are now occurring on daily basis
in most of the main roads linking the districts of Dhusamareb and
Abudwaq, EI-Bur and EI-Dher, Beletuein and Qodqod, Guri-EI and
Balanballe, and Adado and Abudwaq.
</P>
<P>
These roads have been re-opened as part of the fruits achieved
through the peace agreements the clansmen reached over their
differences early in the year.
</P>
<P>
The regional officials especially worry about the possible
ways their areas could be de-mined once and for all since many of
the militiamen who planted the mines are not either alive or away
from the area without leaving behind any kind of a trace or a map
for the mine fields nor the quantity which they had planted.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 land mines are believed to have been planted in
a road between Beletuein and Gobane alone, A very small area not
larger than 10 square km.
</P>
<P>
In one of the latest incidents, 20 camels were perished after
they hit a land mine near Dhusamareb district this week according
to the governor, Yussuf Hassan Eyow. Several women who suffered
the land mine shrapnel are now being treated in the hospital of
the town.
</P>
<P>
The district commissioner of Galhareri in Galgudud region,
Abdi Musa Assir, said the most vulnerable in his area are the
children who sometimes come across and collect the rain-exhumed
mines and play them with.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Constructs 100 Major Docks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- China now has 100 large- and
medium-sized docks, with a total of 3.13 million DWT.
</P>
<P>
With the development of the ship repair industry, China has
built thirty new docks during the past decade, with a total of
over two million DWT. This has greatly increased China's
competitive edge in the world's ship repair industry.
</P>
<P>
China's docks are mainly located in cities such as Dalian,
Shanghai, Guangzhou, and in Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Experts point out that better dock facilities are still
needed, and that it is essential to establish more shipyards and
docks at sites with favorable water and port conditions.
</P>
<P>
The 10,000-ton-class large docks in China are believed to have
a total of 2.98 million DWT, accounting for five percent of the
world's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
