<HEADLINE> South China's Guangzhou Reports 11.9 Percent Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product of
Guangzhou, capital of south China's prospering Guangdong Province,
grew 11.9 percent on a yearly basis in the first six months of
this year.
</P>
<P>
This growth rate is higher than those of Beijing, Shanghai and
Tianjin, three of China's most important cities.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's GDP totaled 79.9 billion yuan for the
first six months of this year, with output value of the
agricultural sector up four percent, industry up 10.95 percent and
 the service sector up 13.57 percent, according to the latest
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's investment in fixed-assets reached 16.2 billion
yuan in the January-June period, up 11.6 percent from the same
period last year. The city's six-month export and retail sales
totaled 4.87 billion U.S. dollars and 43.2 billion yuan, up 2.4 and
13 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Between January and June, Guangzhou utilized 1.74
billion US dollars in overseas investment, a surge of 24.5
percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also indicate that Guangzhou's per capita
disposable income reached 5,807.9 yuan in the first half of this
year, an increase of 13.1 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's retail price index declined 2.6 percent while the
consumer price index, which also covers the cost of services,
edged down 0.9 percent in the first six months.
</P>
<P>
Also in the first half of this year, Guangzhou sold commercial
housing with a combined area of 1.25 million sq m, a jump of 69.5
percent from a year ago. The housing sales turnover rocketed 80.6
percent on a yearly basis to 7.09 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, Guangzhou residents had a total of 169.6
billion yuan in outstanding bank deposits, a rise of 15.3 billion
yuan from the end of last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
