<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Civil Helicopter Market has Bright Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- By the year 2005, China will have
72 to 114 helicopters for civil use, said Shen Yuankang, deputy
director of Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC) recently.
</P>
<P>
China first put helicopters into civil use in 1965. By the end
of 1997, China had nine aviation enterprises using 68 helicopters
of 13 different types, and 256 licensed helicopter pilots.
</P>
<P>
Over 95 percent of China's helicopters are imported, mainly
from Europe, Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Shen Yuankang also pointed out that plans for the manufacture
of helicopters in China have now begun to take shape, though
compared with developed countries China still lags behind in
engineering technology and applications for helicopters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Postmen on Strike for Higher Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Most postal services are
paralyzed in India Friday as an indefinite national strike by more
than 500,000 postal employees for higher pay entered the second
day.
</P>
<P>
About 90 percent of the postal employees stayed away from work
in most states, according to organizers of the strike, the
National Federation of Postal Employees (NFPE) and the Federation
of National Postal Organizations.
</P>
<P>
The two major unions listed nine demands including improved
pay-scales and revision of bonus formula while Communications
Minister Sushma Swaraj appealed to the employees to end the
strike, saying their demands were being considered.
</P>
<P>
The strike disrupted postal services across the country
including collection of letters, sorting, transmission to
outstation posts, booking of registered letters, parcels and other
articles, speed post services for 75 cities and money order
services, the Hindu daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said postal workers had submitted a 10-point charter
of demands last year to the Department of Posts and had
subsequently called off a similar indefinite strike last November
following assurances from the government.
</P>
<P>
However, they said, neither the government nor the department
concerned looked into their demands, forcing them to go on strike.
</P>
<P>
NFPE and FNPO representatives held one-hour talks with Swaraj
Thursday night but in vain, said NFPE Secretary General R. L.
Bhattacharya, who threatened to intensify the strike.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, services in all government hospitals and
dispensaries in New Delhi came to a virtual standstill Thursday as
70,000 employees began a two-day total strike to press their
various demands.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
