<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hidden Employment A Burden to Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Hidden employment has become a
burden to State-owned enterprises, today's China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
For example, 42-year-old Song was a laid-off worker of a food
processing factory in Beijing and the same time works as a
temporary cleaner. If she doesn't report her new job to her
employer, she can still receive a monthly subsidy of 200 yuan (26
US dollars) from her original workplace.
</P>
<P>
According to the Daily, such hidden employment is not uncommon
in China's State-owned enterprises, as the social security system
is still incomplete in the country at the moment.
</P>
<P>
Currently, old-age pensions and medical and unemployment
insurance are all offered by State-owned firms.
</P>
<P>
Under the government sponsored re-employment program,
loss-ridden State-owned enterprises are required to set up
re-employment centers, partly to ensure laid-off workers a basic
livelihood while they are unemployed.
</P>
<P>
As a result, workers, after getting their pink slips, prefer to
straddle the fence-both registering as unemployed at the
reemployment center and also hurrying to find a new job on their
own.
</P>
<P>
"We have to spend more than two million yuan every year to
ensure a basic living to laid-offs, even though we know that most
of them have other sources of income", the Daily quoted Han Gang,
head of the re-employment center of Beijing Yili Food Processing
Co. as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
