<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo on Falling Banking Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled in Tokyo Friday as
heavy selling of banking in the afternoon triggered a widespread drop
in stock prices.
</P>
<P>
Comments made around noon by Yasuhisa Shiozaki, Japan's
parliamentary vice finance minister, that operators and shareholders
of failed banks "must take responsibility" fueled stronger fears over
Japan's fragile banking system and led to a sell-off of banking
shares.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange plummeted 356.89 points, or 2.17
percent, from Thursday's close to finish at 16,090.06.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 20.78 points or 1.65 percent to 1,241.50.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 570 million
shares from Thursday's 397.70 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was Friday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the Nikkei's 356-point fall was natural, considering
the index climbed 1,300 points last week, mainly due to expectations
of the government cutting income taxes permanently next year to boost
domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, losers outweighed
gainers 895 to 268, with 105 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
