<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Former Chief of General Staff Won't Die </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's military rulers have
decided to save the lives of former chief of general staff
Lt.-Gen. Oladipo Diya and others sentenced to death for
involvement in a fouled coup plot last December, the State Radio
reported Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
But the highest authorities, after two days of intensive
meeting which ended Thursday night, failed to provide its final
decision on the remaining part of the country's political
transition program.
</P>
<P>
Diya and five others, including two former ministers, were
sentenced to death on charges of treason by a special military
tribunal in April, and execution has since been pending on the
decision of the highest authority.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Ruling Council (PRC), the highest
decision-making body, reviewed the death sentences at its meeting
in the last two days, decided to exempt the six people from death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
The PRC decided to change the death sentences of Diya and two other
former ministers to 25 years imprisonment, the report said,
quoting a PRC spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The death sentence of three others were commuted to 20 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
On the much-expected final decision on how the military
government is to do to push its transition to civil rule program
forward, the spokesman said the head of state will give another
nationwide broadcast on that very soon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
