<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 07:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain To Replace Norway in Peacekeeping in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Troops from Italy and Spain appear
to be heading the list to replace Norwegian soldiers serving with
the United Nations peacekeeping forces in south Lebanon, the Daily
Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a Spain source as saying that the U.N. in New
York has asked Spain to replace the Norwegians working in the
U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (Unifil).
</P>
<P>
Norway last month announced that it would decrease its
600-strong battalion by two thirds at the end of this year,
claiming it could no longer attract sufficient numbers of
volunteers for the peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-strong Unifil was established in 1978 after Israel's
first invasion of Lebanon with the aim of confirming the
withdrawal of Israeli forces and restoring international peace and
security.
</P>
<P>
Israel has long complained Unifil has been ineffective in
protecting its northern border from Lebanese guerrillas' attack.
</P>
<P>
But Lebanon always speaks highly of the role the forces have
played in safeguarding the security and peace across the border
and hoped that it would stay in the region until the Israeli
pullout from its occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
guerrillas attack.
</P>
<P>
The Norway's plan to reduce its soldiers in Lebanon has
prompted the concern of Lebanese government and local residents.
</P>
<P>
They fear that the reduction would eventually lead to the
disbandment of the forces and facilitate the Israeli attack on the
south.
</P>
<P>
The paper also predicted that other than Spain, the most
likely candidate to replace Norwegian soldiers is Italy, which
has considerable peacekeeping experience in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Italy is already represented in Unifil by the 44 pilots and
ground crew of Italair, the peacekeepers' airborne wing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Promises to Help Improve Africa's Civil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States government is
prepared to work with African governments in partnership to
improve their aviation and transportation infrastructures, a U.S.
official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of Transportation Rodneyx Slater, who arrived
in Harare Thursday evening to attend a one-day conference for
east and Southern African transportation ministers Friday said
U.S. government had set aside a budget of over one million U.S.
Dollars to help African countries in improving their airways to
meet international standards.
</P>
<P>
More funds, he said, were however needed to achieve the goal
of improving Africa's transportation infrastructure and airlines,
the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Some African countries that have achieved the status of safe
and efficient aviation systems are Ghana, South Africa, Senegal
and Ethiopia, whose national airlines now fly directly to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The one-day conference would discuss the implementation of the
"Africa Safe Skies Initiative" launched recently by the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
"A safe and efficient aviation system is essential for
Zimbabwe as well as other mighty African nations as we access the
markets in the world," said Slater, "the U.S. needs to work with
African governments to make their skies more safe."  
</P>
</TEXT>
