<HEADLINE> Warner Generates Huge Revenues from Selling DVDs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Warner Brothers, one of the
giant movie-makers in Hollywood, has generated more than 110
million U.S. dollars from selling new digital videodiscs, or DVDs,
according to reports reaching here late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Warren Lieberfarb, president of Home Video
(a unit of Warner Brothers), disclosed the figure at a working
luncheon with software dealers in Las Vegas, where a trade show
was going on.
</P>
<P>
He said Warner Brothers and several other studios in Hollywood
began selling DVDs in seven test markets in the spring of 1997
with a national launch last summer.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes DVD can reach a penetration level of 10
percent of U.S. households by 2002.
</P>
<P>
DVD is a new technology designed to play back movies, much like
videotapes play in VCRs. But the new digital medium offers a
crisper picture and clearer sound.
</P>
<P>
Many experts believe DVDs will eventually replace VCRs in most
U.S. homes. Lieberfarb said DVD can become a long-lasting product
in the marketplace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
