<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Leaders Urge Development of Social Sciences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the prestigious
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS) said here today that
President Jiang Zemin and other Chinese leaders have recently
urged the greater development of social sciences.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, he said that Jiang has conveyed
his greetings to researchers at the CASS and instructed that this
sector become a more flourishing one.
</P>
<P>
Li Tieying, new CASS president and a member of the Political
Bureau of the Communist Party of China Central Committee, has
also expressed his hope that research work be stepped up for
China's invigoration in the 21st century, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
These developments show that esteem for intellectuals has
reached a new level, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Their social status rose in the late 1970s when Deng Xiaoping
decided that intellectuals should play a significant role in the
country's modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, a widespread debate on the criterion of truth
20 years ago, which laid the foundation for China's reform and
opening, has demonstrated that social sciences are vital to
the evolution of human race.
</P>
<P>
Li asked the CASS to attain a level equal to the best research
institutes in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, Marxism should be adhered to by the
researchers, who at the same time must create an open and free
academic environment by further emancipating minds.
</P>
<P>
The CASS spokesman said that the 21-year-old academy, with
3,000 researchers, has decided that 98 programs should receive
special subsidies to increase pure academic research and provide
practical suggestions for decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
These subjects include China's economic growth mode, an
economic history of the People's Republic, modern Chinese,
archaeology, forecasts of the Chinese economy and social
development, and the welfare system in state enterprises, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Observers to Arrive in Cambodia for Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 10 (Xinhua) -- About 470 international
observers are expected to arrive in Cambodia next week to oversee
the country's general elections on July 26, according to the U.N.
Electoral Assistance Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The first 22 observers will arrive from Canada Sunday, followed
by delegations from more than 30 countries and NGOs throughout the
week. Eight Chinese observers will arrive on July 14.
</P>
<P>
The observers will be divided into 235 two-person mobile
monitoring teams, which will each visit about six polling stations
on the election day. They will get a view of 1,300-1,500 stations,
or about 10 percent of all polling booths.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Joint International Observer Group, the umbrella
organization for all international observers, will have enough
monitors to judge whether the elections are free and fair.
</P>
<P>
The international observers will cooperate with 500,000
Cambodian observers, who are expected to be posted at most polling
booths.
</P>
<P>
However, some political parties and human rights groups called
for still more foreign observers, saying that the presence of more
foreign observers is very important to the confidence of the
voters, who are evidently concerned whether the elections will be
free, fair and credible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
