<HEADLINE> Philippine Army Warns Rebels of Continued Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine army's Sixth
Infantry Division Friday vowed to continue its assault against
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebels in Pigcawayan,
Cotabato, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Major Rosque Garingalao, spokesman of the division, made the
warning one day after government troops and MILF rebels clashed
anew in the area.
</P>
<P>
Skirmishes in Pigcawayan started early Thursday after
patrolling government troops were ambushed by heavily-armed
rebels, Garingalao said.
</P>
<P>
He said the army was forced to use attack helicopters and heavy
artillery as some 200 rebels resisted with machine-guns and other
high-power firearms.
</P>
<P>
Garingalao claimed that there were no casualties on the
government side despite a whole-day gun battle Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, MILF Vice Chairman for Military Affairs Al Haj Murad
appealed to the military to stop air strikes and artillery
shelling, saying local civilians were severely affected by the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
As of Friday, some 1,000 residents have reportedly fled to
safer places to avoid being caught in the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, currently the largest rebel group in the country, has
been engaged in peace talks with the government for the past few
years, but the two parties have made little progress toward
reaching a final peace agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
