<HEADLINE> Tyson Has to Apply for License in Person </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- On the first day Mike Tyson
could apply for a new license back to the ring, Newada boxing
officials made it clear Thursday they want to hear from Tyson
directly before doing anything.
</P>
<P>
"I want to hear from Mike directly," said Marc Ratner,
executive director of the Nevada Athletic Commission. "I will need
to talk to him before we do anything."
</P>
<P>
A year ago, Tyson was fined 3 million U.S. dollars and his
license was revoked after biting Holyfield's ears. Thursday was
the date when Tyson was eligible to apply for a new license that
would allow him to return any competitions.
</P>
<P>
But no such request had been made by the time commission
offices closed for the day. "As far as I know, nobody has given us
anything in writing to indicate they are representing Mike Tyson,"
said James Nave, a commission member.
</P>
<P>
Tyson has split from promoter Don King and his former
co-managers, claiming they took millions of dollars from him.
Recently, fight manager Shelly Finkel said he represents the
former world heavyweight champion.
</P>
<P>
Finkel said last month that Tyson would apply for a new license
this month, with plans to fight in October or November.
</P>
<P>
If the five-member commission refuses to give Tyson a new
license, Tyson has to wait for another year to reapply for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
