<HEADLINE> Ukraine, NATO to Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine and the North Atlatic Treaty
Organization (NATO) have agreed to expand their cooperation within
the framework of the NATO-Ukraine partnership charter.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Thursday by Ukranian President Leonid Kuchma
and NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
Solana, who is on a visit to Ukraine to for the first
anniversary of the signing of the charter, held talks with Kuchma
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Solana told reporters that Ukraine will play a key role in the
establishment of the new framework for security in Europe.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Secretary of Ukranian State Committee on
Security and Defense Vladimir Gorbulin, and Defense Minister
Oleksandr Kuzmuk, Solana said there was a bright future for
cooperation between NATO and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Gorbulin said Ukraine is about to purchase new technologies
from NATO members.
</P>
<P>
Kuzmuk proposed that NATO make use of the exercise grounds in
Ukraine to carry out military training.
</P>
<P>
During his tour, Solana also met with Ukranian Foreign Minister
Boris Tarasyuk and Chairman of the Supreme Soviet of Ukraine,
Alexandr Tkachenko.
</P>
<P>
Since the signing of the NATO-Ukraine partnership charter,
Ukranian leaders have repeatedly said the development of
Ukraine-NATO ties was a major step for Ukraine in joining the new
security framework in Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
