<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Reports Steady Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Beijing, the Chinese capital,
scored comparatively rapid economic growth during the first six
months of the year, according to information released at the
ongoing meeting covering the local economic situation.
</P>
<P>
The city's gross domestic product (GDP) for the January-June
period hit 83.9 billion yuan (10.1 billion US dollars), up 9.1
percent on last year's same period in terms of constant prices.
</P>
<P>
The service sector reported the most rapid growth in output,
with the total value-added for the industry rising by 13.3 percent
to 45.87 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Zhenyu, director of the Beijing Municipal Planning
Commission, attributed the growth to increased investment. Fixed
asset investments during the period stood at 32.46 billion yuan,
up 28.3 percent on the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
Local retail sales grew by 10.7 percent during the first half
of the year, with the total volume hitting 55.44 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by Beijing Customs show the January-May
import-export value climbed by 11.4 percent to 2.36 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Beijing approved 329 overseas-funded enterprises during the
period, with total contracted foreign investment standing at 1.2
billion US dollars. 
</P>
