<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Cautiously Welcomes Group's Statement on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian government Thursday
cautiously welcomed the statement issued by the six-nation Contact
Group on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano said in a statement that
Albania supported the international community in its continuous
efforts to seek a peaceful solution to the Kosovo problem.
</P>
<P>
During the Bonn meeting on Wednesday, the Contact Group called
for an immediate cease-fire in Kosovo to pave the way for
continuous dialogue on the future of the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
The group also agreed to seek a resolution of the United
Nations Security Council to press for this demand, and guarantee
the safety of international observers operating in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Nano said Albania welcomes the decision made by the Contact
Group on the involvement of international mediators in the
negotiations between Belgrade and the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
However, Nano said it was too early to hold talks on the status
of Kosovo under the prevailing situation in which the Serbian
authorities had not withdrawn their troops from Kosovo, nor
stopped the oppression.
</P>
<P>
Describing the withdrawal of the Serbian forces as the core
issue for a final solution to the Kosovo crisis, Nano said he did
not see any positive changes in Kosovo because Belgrade still
adhered to its previous stands.
</P>
<P>
The international community should not get excited by sporadic
moves taken by Belgrade, he added.
</P>
<P>
Nano also proposed linking the restoration of Yugoslav seats in
some world organizations with its efforts to end the Kosovo
conflict. The efforts must be based on the respect of the will of
the Kosovo people, and on international norms.
</P>
<P>
A report from Belgrade said the Yugoslav authorities would not
reject the Contact Group's proposal on the determination of the
status of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Austrian Foreign Secretary Albert Roan, who
is on a visit to Yugoslavia, as saying that Yugoslavia is enacting
a scheme on the autonomous status for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia would act with caution on the issue, Roan added.
</P>
<P>
During talks between Roan and Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivorad
Jovanovic, both sides noted that a lasting and peaceful solution
to the Kosovo problem would come only through unconditional
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the population in
the Serbian province of Kosovo, are seeking independence from
Belgrade which stripped Kosovo of its autonomy in 1991. Hundreds
of people have died since February, 1998 when armed conflicts
escalated tensions there into a crisis.
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
