<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Enforces New Law Combating Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian parliament Thursday enacted
a new act, giving the law-enforcing agencies more teeth against
money laundering.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law which revoked the 1996 law on prevention of
money laundering, those engaging in money laundering are liable to
an imprisonment of three to 12 years, a fine of up to 30 million
leva (about 16,600 U.S. dollars) and confiscation of all or part
of their properties.
</P>
<P>
Officials who violate the law will face a sentence of up to one
year in prison and be fined 1 to 3 million leva (about 550 to
1,650 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A financial investigation bureau will be set up under the
Finance Ministry to process information about financial
transactions carried out by banks, insurance companies, investment
groups, privatization funds, brokers and other economic entities.
</P>
<P>
They are obliged to keep information on any client involved in
a transaction worth more than 30 million leva and inform the
bureau if suspicion arises about money laundering activities.
</P>
<P>
But the requirements do not apply to political parties and some
non-profit organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
