<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs Social Sector Reform Projects in Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Thursday approved
two interest-free credits totaling 30 million U.S. dollars
equivalent for Macedonia's projects for social sector reform.
</P>
<P>
The first credit of 29 million dollars will be used to assist
its social sector adjustment. This project will support measures
to help improve the long term financial solvency of social sector
programs, reduce labor market distortions, and reduce poverty by
improving the quality and targeting efficiency of social sector
programs.
</P>
<P>
The other credit of 1 million dollars will be provided for the
country's pension reform technical assistance project. This
project will support the design and implementation of Macedonia's
pension policy reforms under the country's Social Sector
Adjustment Program.
</P>
<P>
The credits will be channeled through the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessional
lending affiliate for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Since joining the World Bank and IDA in 1993, Macedonia has
received some 405 million dollars in commitment for 14 projects,
including those okayed Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
