<HEADLINE> Swedish, Finnish Coast Guards Clear up Oil Spill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Swedish and Finnish coast guards,
on Thursday, were cleaning up an oil spill nine kilometers long
and 50 meters wide near the island of Aland, off the central
Swedish coast.
</P>
<P>
They were also investigating a Liberian gas tanker over the
spillage.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the coast guards said the spillage was reported
late on Wednesday by a German aircraft flying into Stockholm's
international airport, Arlanda.
</P>
<P>
The oil slick had moved south and was now near Aland and the
mainland port of Gisslehamn, 100 kilometers north of
Stockholm. Finnish coast guards joined the clean-up after the oil
slick reached Finnish waters.
</P>
<P>
According to the coast guards spokesman, the oil is not
threatening the coastline and the clean-up process is relatively
simple and will be completed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish coast guard had stopped a Liberian gas tanker,
suspected of leaking the oil, at the northern Swedish port of Umea.
</P>
<P>
Several oil samples were taken from the ship. If the ship is
proved to be the culprit, it will be billed about 7500 U.S.dollars
for the clean-up operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
