<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Libya Sign Accord to Normalize Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Italian Foreign Ministry said
Thursday that Italy had signed an accord with Libya to put behind
"the negative heritage of the past" and normalize their bilateral
ties.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry said in a statement that the accord was
signed by Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini and Mustafa
el-Muntasser, secretary of the Libyan People's Committee for
Foreign Relations and International Cooperation, after a meeting
here Saturday of a mixed Italian-Libyan commission.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Italy and Libya would make efforts to
finally put an end to "the negative heritage of the past" and
"establish a new and more dynamic course in relations between
their two countries," the ministry statement said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also promised in their accord that they would
make joint efforts to fight against terrorist activities in all
forms, ensure the non-proliferation of weapons of mass
destruction, and reduce the destabilizing factors in the region.
</P>
<P>
Among differences between Italy and Libya, which was an Italian
colony from 1911 to 1943, has been the questions of financial
compensation for the colonial period, and removal of the land
mines left over there in Libya from the wartime period.
</P>
<P>
In the just signed agreement, Rome expressed "regrets for the
colonial period," and would provide for demining Libyan terrain of
World War II-era land mines, as well as the building of a center
to care for land mine victims.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Foreign Ministry said in the statement that its
policy vis-a-vis Libya is part of its overall policy toward the
Mediterranean region, which is aiming at eliminating all sorts of
antagonism and tension, and establishing cooperative relations
among countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Dini said in an interview with the Italian newspaper La
Repubblica (The Republic) Thursday that the defrosting of
relations with Libya is of great significance to the security in
the Mediterranean, because it meant the removal of tension in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Despite their past discords, Rome and Tripoli have established
strong economic and trade ties. In 1997, Italian imports, mostly
oil, totalled almost 4 billion U.S. dollars, while exports to
Libya reached about 880 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
