<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Parliament Prorogues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The budget session of the
Bangladeshi parliament, the Jatiya Sangsad, ended here Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
The parliament went into the budget session, the ninth session
of the country's Seventh Parliament, on June 10. The national
budget for the 1998-99 fiscal year beginning July 1 was placed
before the House by Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria the next
day and was passed on June 30.
</P>
<P>
In her winding up speech at the parliament, Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina called upon opposition members of parliament to
attend parliamentary proceedings regularly.
</P>
<P>
"She (Leader of Opposition in parliament Begum Khaleda Zia) has
so far neither attended any meeting of the Jatiya Sangsad Business
Advisory Committee nor she attended the proceedings of the House
regularly -- giving a clear impression that she does not believe
in parliamentary system," Hasina said.
</P>
<P>
The major opposition the Bangladesh Nationalist Party walked
out of the eighth session of the parliament in early May when
three hill district council bills designed to give legal effect to
the Chittagong Hill Tracts peace treaty, signed between the
government and the hill tribals last December, were taken up for
consideration.
</P>
<P>
The BNP members of parliament, accusing the Speaker of failing
to maintain "neutrality" and protested against "limited
discussion" on the bills, have since remained absence from
parliament proceedings for most the time.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chief Whip of the Opposition Khandaker Delwar
Hossain on Thursday urged the Treasury Bench, particularly the
Leader of the House (Hasina) to "behave in a manner" that would
make the parliament effective.
</P>
<P>
"Her language should not be a language of attack or quarrel,"
Delwar said.
</P>
<P>
"Greater responsibility lies on the stronger shoulder, the
greater leader... leader of the house," and "It is the duty of
the leader of the House to unite the whole country and invite us
(Opposition) in the process," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
