<HEADLINE> hke071012 -Sri Lanka's Exports Increase in 1st 5 Months This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's exports during the
first five months of this year went up by 15.2 percent to 1.95
billion U.S. dollars from 1.70 billion dollars recorded in the
corresponding period of 1997, according to Central Bank Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the higher growth in May this year compared to
April had helped cumulative figures to look impressive. On a
monthly basis, the export performance in May was up by 23 percent
compared to the level in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Export growth during the first four months in 1998 was 13.1
percent in rupee terms and 4.9 percent in the U.S. dollar terms.
</P>
<P>
The growth is considered significant since it was from a higher
base of 1997. Last year the country's exports grew by over 13
percent compared to 7.6 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that the export performance was encouraging in
view of the negative export growth experienced by some of the
southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) grew by 5.8 percent in
the first quarter of 1998 over the corresponding period of last
year which was 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank is monitoring the economic performance on a
quarterly basis now as a prudent measure to provide an update on
overall and sectoral trends of the economy.
</P>
<P>
During the first five months of 1998 agricultural exports
achieved the highest growth of 25.6 percent supported by the tea
sector performance of 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
Rubber exports dropped by 44.8 percent and coconut dropped by
49 percent. Industrial exports increased by 13.7 percent and
textiles by 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
Petroleum products increased by 9 percent but mineral exports
dropped by 35 percent with a 37 percent decline in gem exports.
</P>
</TEXT>
