<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's National Park Free From Attacks: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 10 (Xinhua) - The authority of Sri Lanka's
National Park at Yala in the deep south, which was harassed by
Tamil rebels last year, Thursday declared the park safe for
visitors, reports reaching here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
(LTTE) infiltrated the park and launched sporadic attacks on
visitors and officials of the park's administration.
</P>
<P>
After the attacks visitors had been afraid to visit the park
where LTTE cadres acted at will.
</P>
<P>
The park's administration was then placed under military
control, with guards stationed in all parts of the park to carry
out regular patrols to prevent LTTE members from penetrating into
the park.
</P>
<P>
The park authority said rumors that the park was still unsafe
were aimed at continuing hunting, cultivation of narcotics and
illicit felling of timber in the park.
</P>
<P>
Such activities have been curbed and now the park is free from
both LTTE rebels and other racketeers, said the reports, adding
that visitors both local and foreign will return as usual to visit
the park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
