<HEADLINE> IMF Urges Laos to Tighten Fiscal Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has suggested that Laos tighten its fiscal and monetary
policies to stop a further fall in the exchange rate, higher
inflation and worsening of its banking system.
</P>
<P>
"Executive directors expressed deep concern about the
deteriorating macro-economic performance in 1997 and 1998 (in
Laos)," the IMF revealed in an annual review, which was available
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Laos' currency kip has depreciated by almost 70 percent to the
U.S. dollar, contributing to a sharp rise in annual inflation
which stood at more than 60 percent in May this year.
</P>
<P>
The IMF review said that it had been a mistake not to introduce
tax measures in last September's budget to improve the tax base
and that their recent implementation would have only a limited
effect on the current year's fiscal performance.
</P>
<P>
It said the monetary policy in 1997 had failed to curb rapid
credit growth, which had fed into higher inflation and a falling
exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
"They (IMF directors) urged the authorities to act quickly to
raise interest rates to positive real levels, and to contain
credit expansion," the review said. 
</P>
