<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Birthing Study Shows Walking No Help in Childbirth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Guidebooks on pregnancy and
childbirth usually recommend walking around to help cut labor
time, but the advice has been knocked down by a new study.
</P>
<P>
Women who pace out their first hours in labor rather than
remaining sitting or lying have no better or worse deliveries than
those who stay put, the report of the New England Journal of
Medicine said.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by the University of Texas Southwestern
Medical Center in Dallas. Over an 11-month period, 1,067 women
with uncomplicated pregnancies took part in the test, with half
randomly assigned to walk during the first hours of active uterine
contractions, the other half to wait things out in their rooms
attended by nurses and aides.
</P>
<P>
Of the 530 women assigned to walk, only 380 did with several
hundred slow steps over about an hour. Those who didn't were too
far advanced in their labor to start out. But walking had no
apparent effect on any significant outcome that could be measured.
</P>
<P>
Those bearing their first child in the two groups spent about
7.5 hours in the early stage of labor and about an hour actually
delivering the baby. Times were reduced but similar for women who
had delivered before.
</P>
<P>
The condition and health of the babies delivered by the two
groups were indistinguishable.
</P>
<P>
The report said that although there is no medical reason for
walking during labor, it does seem, for some women, to improve
their satisfaction with the labor experience.
</P>
<P>
Walking around, or at least staying in an upright position,
have become hallmarks of most of the prepared childbirth systems
promoted and taught today. Several popular guidebooks mention
research that indicates walking helps cut labor time by an hour,
or 30 percent, or lessens dependence on drugs.
</P>
<P>
Doctors participating in the new study said the trials that led
to the earlier advice were done nearly two decades ago and
involved just 82 women.
</P>
<P>
Two other random trials published about the same time,
involving 670 women, found no difference in labor time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Excavate Ruins of Ancient Ordnance Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Chongqing
Municipality plans to excavate the ruins of the nation's first
ordnance plant which dates to Southern Song Dynasty (1127-1279
A.D.).
</P>
<P>
The ruins, which cover some 3,000 sq.m. on an ancient
battlefield, will be developed into a new tourism site..
</P>
<P>
Archeologists note that stone-throwing devices and pitted stone
rollers for producing gunpowder have been unearthed at the site,
some 90 percent of which remains buried.
</P>
<P>
Furthers excavation efforts are expected to yield a wide array
of relics.
</P>
<P>
Experts from China's Academy of Military Science, Military
Museum and various cultural relics departments note that the
discovery will be of great importance for further research into
the nation's military history and the development of weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
