<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers to Popularize Use of Clean Fuel Made of Straw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A gasified straw fuel is being
recognized as an environmental friendly and cheap energy for daily
use in China's rural area, according to a meeting source here in
east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
Jointly held by the Ministry of Science and Technology, the
Ministry of Agriculture and the State General Administration of
Environmental Protection, the meeting voiced that the use of
gasified straw fuel can avoid waste and pollution resulted from
straw burning.
</P>
<P>
Straw is one of the most popular traditional burning stuffs for
rural living. In China, a largest agricultural country in the
world, 600 million tons of straw of various kinds are yielded
every year, with 200 million tons burnt for cooking.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in some better-off rural areas where coal brick and
LPG are becoming popular fuel stuffs, piling straws, weighing 100
million tons, are just burnt in the fields every year, emiting
huge smoke into the air.
</P>
<P>
Black smoke produced by such practices in Chengdu, capital of
Sichuan Province caused suspending and canceling of 61 flights in
the Shuangliu International Airport in May. It has been the most
serious flight delay accident in China which is caused by
pollution.
</P>
<P>
To this count, the state environment protection department has
vowed to coordinate the spreading of the new clean fuel. A
professional estimate suggests that one million tons of dust
pollutant and 600,000 tons of sulphur dioxide can be eliminated,
should a tenth of the villages in China burn straw gas in stead of
using coal.
</P>
<P>
A straw gasifying facility consumes 200 tons of straw and
generates 400,000 cu.m. gas fuel a year equivalent to the energy
produced by 192 tons of coal or 36 tons of LPG. The gas costs a
household 33.9 yuan a month nearly as cheap as coal and 40 percent
cheaper than LPG.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey made in Shandong shows that 75 percent of the
surveyed farmers preferred straw gas. So far, the province has set
up 54 of the said facilities benefiting 8,000 households. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
