<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Latin America has become the only solid market for
Chilean exports since the fall in international demand after the
Asian crisis last July.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank said that exports to Latin America grew 6.8
percent to 1.4 billion U.S. dollars between January and May of
this year, compared with the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sales to Asia dropped by 26 percent to 1.87 billion dollars,
while exports to Europe were down 0.5 percent to 1.8 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The contribution of the hotel and restaurant
sectors to the gross domestic product (GDP) almost doubled between
1986 and 1997, a report of the Argentine Hotel and Restaurant
Entrepreneurial Federation said.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that employment in the sector increased by 2.1
percent between 1991 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panamanian President Ernesto Perez Balladares
announced a minimum salary increase for private enterprise workers
of 6 U.S. cents per hour, raising the average minimum salary in
Panama to 208 dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombian exports to Venezuela grew 69
percent during the first quarter of this year, the highest
increase in past years.
</P>
<P>
Colombian Foreign Trade Minister Carlos Ronderos said that by
the end of this year the bilateral trade was expected to amount to
three billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Assets injected into the Brazilian banking system
by foreign institutions were up from 23.56 billion dollars in 1994
to 98.38 billion dollars in 1997, a 137.57 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of foreign banks in Brazil increased from
32 in 1994 to 42 in 1997, making up 23 percent of the total banks
in Brazil. The number of the foreign banks is expected to amount
to 40 percent in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian exports of motor vehicles amounted to 770
million dollars in the first five months of this year, a 124
increase over the same period last year, while the imports of cars
reached one billion dollars, a 12.36 rise.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Costa Rican Salaries National Council decided
to increase the salaries of civil servants by 6.10 percent, after
intense negotiations between the government and unions.
</P>
<P>
The salaries of civil servants are adjusted twice a year, in
accordance with the laws of this Central American country.
</P>
<P>
The first readjustment went into effect on January 1, and the
second on July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
