<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Visits Fire-Stricken Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Thursday visited fire-stricken Florida, where he declared 34
counties disaster areas and announced new federal assistance for
the local people suffering from the fires.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also praised the firefighters for their work in keeping
the wildfires from consuming whole communities in the state.
</P>
<P>
The president met with firefighters and local residents who
lost everything in Volusia County, which was hit hard by fires.
Many of the families in the county were renting and had no
insurance, and are now living in hotels or with relatives.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very sorry for what you're going through," Clinton told
them.
</P>
<P>
The federal assistance that Clinton announced includes a Labor
Department grant of up to 1 million U.S. dollars for hiring 200
temporary workers to help clean up charred areas, restore roads
and assist at shelters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the entire state is now eligible for emergency
loans through the Department of Agriculture to help compensate for
the loss of 63,000 hectares of forest worth 185 million dollars,
and another 243,000 hectares of crops by an ongoing drought.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton said the main purpose of his visit was to praise
the more than 7,000 firefighters and volunteers from most of the
50 states.
</P>
<P>
"You did show our country at its best," Clinton said. "You
showed people what the meaning of community is and why we really
do depend on each other."
</P>
<P>
Wildfires have scorched more than 196,000 hectares since late
May. At least 350 homes and businesses were destroyed, three
people died and more than 100 others injured.
</P>
<P>
It has cost more than 104 million dollars to fight the blazes,
which have caused about 276 million dollars in damage.
</P>
<P>
Florida Governor Lawton Chiles said that while the fires are
largely out, there is still a threat of flare-ups because the
state still needs rain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
