<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Bans Raw Seafood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGDONG, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Weeks of flooding and sweltering
heat have forced the Guangzhou municipal government to issue a
three-month ban starting this week on eating sashimi in the city,
China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The first of its kind in this capital of south China's
Guangdong Province, the ban is valid from July 3 to September
30. Any violators will be severely punished, according to the
official notice.
</P>
<P>
The notice blames raw seafood as a key factor in the increasing
number of cases of cholera, dysentery and other widespread
infectious intestinal diseases appearing this summer.
</P>
<P>
Easily infected by bacteria that flourish in the summer heat,
all seafood now has to be served after thorough cooking, including
shellfish.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the chance of seafood becoming infected is much
higher this year, as the province is now challenged by the worst
flood that may occur once a century.
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted that the ban will be another strike against the
local fishing industry, which has already been severely damaged by
the provincial floods during the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Also, the ban makes no exception for sashimi imported from
abroad, which will force local expensive restaurants and hotels to
strike the popular dishes off their menus.
</P>
<P>
Officials warned it's very dangerous for sashimi lovers to eat any
of this favored delicacy in this season, even if they go to other
cities in the Pearl River Delta for their feasts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
