<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Zhu Rongji visited Hubei and Hunan provinces over
the last four days to look into flood relief work and preparations
there.
</P>
<P>
He was accompanied by Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao, head of the
State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters, and went to
Jingzhou in Hubei on the morning of July 6 to inspect the banks of
the Jingjiang section of the Yangtze River and dykes near Hubei's
capital, Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
-- The Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC)
officially set up its large enterprise work commission yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo, head of the work commission, spoke at
the commission's work conference for officials from large
enterprises in Beijing. Wu said that the commission is a great way
to speed up reforms at state-owned enterprises and to establish an
administrative system for the socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
(MOFTEC) announced yesterday that China will take temporary
anti-dumping measures against newsprint originated from Canada,
the Republic of Korea (ROK) and the United States beginning on
July 10.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC officially began investigating cases involving the
alleged dumping of newsprint from these countries on December 10,
1997, in accordance with China's anti-dumping and anti-subsidy
regulations.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing met with Bill Emmott,
editor-in-chief of the British Economist weekly, an economic
magazine, and his party yesterday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
-- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, met yesterday
with a Japanese delegation from the city of Kobe headed by mayor
Sasayama Kazutoshi.
</P>
<P>
Li offered his congratulations on the 25th anniversary of the
forging of the sister-city ties between China's Tianjin City and
Kobe, the first of its kind between China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang Guoqiang made the statement
at the routine press conference yesterday that Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat will visit China as from July 13 at the
invitation of Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
-- China's new Ministry of Information Industry (MII) plans
gradually to open up the country's telecommunications market to
the outside world.
</P>
<P>
-- According to a recent re-organization plan, MII will have 13
departments and one of their major functions will be to make
China's telecommunications industry more international.  
</P>
</TEXT>
