<DOCNO> XIE19980710.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, July 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A strong earthquake measured at a preliminary
magnitude of 6.4 struck Anchorage and its surrounding areas of
southern Alaska Thursday morning, sending people into the streets.
</P>
<P>
There were no immediate reports of any serious damage or
injuries. The quake was centered 200 kilometers southwest of
Anchorage. It was felt in Anchorage, Kodiak, Fairbanks, Palmer
and Cordova, shaking an area about 360 kilometers by 800
kilometers, reports from Anchorage said. (US-Earthquake)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said
Thursday that the United States would continue to deploy its
37,000 combat troops in the Korean peninsula even if the two
Koreas were to be unified in the future.
</P>
<P>
"We think that should continue. And that should continue even
if there is... a unification of the two Koreas," he said at a
joint news conference with his visiting South Korean counterpart
Cheon Yong-Taek. (US-S.Korea-Troops)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- World population will reach 6 billion in
1999, 12 years after it totaled 5 billion in 1987, according to
the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
World inhabitants amount to 5.9 billion today, with an increase
of 3 persons every second, or 222,000 daily or 81 million yearly.
</P>
<P>
Global population reached the 1 billion level by 1800, but it
took 130 years to reach 2 billion by 1930. The number reached 3
billion by 1960 and 14 years later, it grew to 4 billion in 1974.
(UN-Population Day)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia Thursday hailed U.S. President Bill Clinton's
decision to visit Moscow regarless of whether Russian parliament
ratifies the second strategic arms reduction treaty.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky told reporters
Thursday that tying up the Russian-U.S. top-level contacts with
the ratification of the START II treaty, as "propagated by some
circles in the U.S.," was counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
Clinton announced last Monday that he would visit Russia in
early September. (Russia-US-START) 
</P>
