<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Powerful Earthquake Shakes Southern Alaska </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A powerful earthquake struck
Anchorage and its surrounding areas of the southern U.S. state of
Alaska Thursday morning, sending people running into the streets,
the U.S. news media reported.
</P>
<P>
There was no serious damage or injuries because of its remote
location.
</P>
<P>
The quake, measured 6.4 on the Richter scale, struck at 11:40
(1940 GMT) and was centered 200 kilometers southwest of Anchorage,
the largest city of the state with a population of 250,000.
</P>
<P>
It was felt in Anchorage, Kodiak, Fairbanks, Palmer and
Cordova, shaking an area about 360 kilometers by 800 kilometers,
but it was centered about 145 kilometers below the surface, the
Tsunami Warming Center in Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
The quake, triggering house alarms and knocking items off
shelves, sent many people in Anchorage rushing to the streets.
But the Tsunami Warning Center said there was no danger of a
tsunami, a giant wave generated by undersea movement of the Earth.
</P>
<P>
Southern Alaska, sitting along the Ring of Fire, an arc of
volcanoes and fault lines stretching along the U.S. West Coast and
into Asia. It is one of the world's most earthquake-prone
regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
