<HEADLINE> Albright Meets Palestinian Delegation over Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on Thursday met with a Palestinian delegation
amid indications that the Clinton administration was nearing the
end of its drive for a second withdrawal of Israeli troops from
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, led by Saed Erekat, a senior Palestinian
negotiator, was sent by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat who
talked on telephone with Albright on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It was said Arafat agreed to a U.S. proposal for the Israeli
troops to withdraw from the 13 percent of territory of the West
Bank at the present stage although he had claimed 97 percent of
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian Cabinet minister said on Thursday the delegation
would not accept any more changes of the U.S. proposal, and Erekat
will listen "but will not renegotiate" over Israel's pullback.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting between Albright and the Palestinian
delegation, State Department spokesman James Rubin said: "We are
clearly in the end game. This cannot go on indefinitely." 
