<HEADLINE> Britain, Peru Agree to Further Bilateral Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and visiting Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori Thursday agreed
to enhance various cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman told reporters that the two leaders
held talks in London early Thursday and "signed a bilateral action
plan setting out how they could strengthen cooperation across the
economic, commercial and cultural spheres".
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that Blair and Fujimori also discussed the
Peruvian economic reforms, Latin America trade liberalization, the
Asian financial crisis and its impact on Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Blair also thanked President Fujimori for the
Peruvian government's efforts in tackling the serious drugs
problems in Peru, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Peru accounts for half of the world's
annual output of cocaine, although the Peruvian government has cut
by half the number of hectares of land devoted to coca leaf
production over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
The British government has reportedly provided some 250 million
pounds (about 410 million U.S. dollars) in aid to Peru to help the
country fund programs to switch to other crops.  
</P>
