<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Continued Efforts Should be Made in Implementing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The goals laid out in the
Platform for Action adopted at the Fourth World Conference and the
Non-governmental Organization Forum on Women held in Beijing in
1995 are still far from being fully achieved and the international
community should make continued efforts in this regard, Chinese
delegate stressed here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the high-level dialogue on world trade sponsored
by the Economic and Social Council of the United Nations, Chinese
Deputy Representative to the United Nations Shen Guofang said the
Beijing Declaration and Platform for Action have laid out the
strategic goals of solving the problems facing women around the
world as well as actions needed in reaching these goals.
</P>
<P>
Shen said governments and non-governmental organizations of
various countries are translating the commitment made then into
action and more and more people have realized that gender
equality is an important yardstick in measuring the progress of
the society.
</P>
<P>
Shen said in order to implement the goals, it is necessary
for the operational activities of the United Nations system to
enhance the policy dialogue and coordination among the various
organizations at the headquarters and U.N. specialized agencies so
that they will act in unison, compliment each other and deepen
the impact of the assistance programs at the country level.
</P>
<P>
Shen said the various proposals and measures by the U.N.
Secretary-General such as capacity building, staff training,
time-bound targets, accountability and evaluation mechanisms are
very necessary.
</P>
<P>
Shen said China fully supports the inclusion of promoting
the advancement of women and emphasizes the role of the resident
coordinator in this respect at the country level so as to
highlight the importance of the promotion of the advancement of
women and truly give expression to the idea of involving the
gender issue in technical cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
