<HEADLINE> Britain Moves to Seek Ceasefire in Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Office minister
Derek Fatchett will travel to Africa next week in an effort to
secure a ceasefire in southern Sudan and try to get more
international aid into the war-stricken country.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett was quoted by Reuters as saying Thursday that he would
fly to Nairobi to meet representatives of the Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA) and then travel to Khartoum to hold talks
with Sudanese Foreign Minister Mustafa Osman Ismail.
</P>
<P>
"A temporary truce in the most hunger-affected areas is
essential if the Sudanese people are to be able to start
rebuilding their lives," Fatchett said.
</P>
<P>
"Agreement on corridors of tranquillity which enable aid to get
through would represent an important step in assisting those most
in need. I shall strongly encourage the parties to accept this
proposal." Fatchett added.
</P>
<P>
However, Fatchett made it clear that a long-term solution could
come only through a sustainable political settlement negotiated
between the conflicting parties in Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
