<HEADLINE> World Cup Refereeing Still Needs Improvement: Blatter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The refereeing in the World Cup finals in
France still needed improvement despite that referees' general
performance had been satisfying, FIFA President Sepp Blatter said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper told a news conference: "Mr. Blatter
said that while FIFA were generally pleased with the standard of
refereeing at the World Cup, more works needed to be done to further
improve standards."
</P>
<P>
FIFA Disciplinary Committee Chairman Pablo Porta of Spain also
praised the World Cup referees in his report in a meeting of the FIFA
World Cup Organizing Committee on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the committee had from time to time used video
evidence to help members better understand what had happened in a case
in point.
</P>
<P>
The committe had been blasted by Blatter earlier this month for
their failure to use video footages to sanction some players for their
unsportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
Blatter has dropped his original proposal to set up a permanent
Executive Board to speed the decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
Instead he now proposed to hold more frequent meetings of the
Executive Committe itself, increasing the frequency to at least four
times a year from only twice as at present.
</P>
<P>
FIFA also said on Thursday that no change would be made on the
General Secretariat for the time being but an outside consultancy
agency would study its current structure and make suggestions on a
possible restructuring.
</P>
<P>
A restructuring, FIFA said, would "make it more functional and
better to reflect FIFA's de facto status as a major service
organization."
</P>
<P>
Blatter also suggested that the timing of future presidential
elections should be changed to avoid a clash with the World Cup
finals.
</P>
<P>
However, such a change would have to require a modification of the
FIFA Statutes by the Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
