<HEADLINE> China's MFN Meets Little Resistance in US Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The renewal of China's MFN
seemed to have met little resistance in a Senate committee
Thursday despite concerns about a massive U.S. trade deficit with
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Key members of the Senate Finance Committee indicated at a
hearing that China's Most Favored Nation (MFN) trading status
should be extended for another year for the sake of U.S.
interests. Critics admitted that they could not gather enough
votes to overturn President Bill Clinton's decision.
</P>
<P>
Clinton proposed to Congress early June that normal trade
relations should be maintained with China, the fourth largest
trading partner of the United States. The Congress has 90 days to
decide if they would go along with the president.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky were present at the hearing, trying to
convince the lawmakers of the importance of normal trade ties with
China. The U.S. is China's second largest trading partner.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that despite differences with China on such
touchy issues as human rights and trade, China's role in the world
economy should not be curbed by imposing high U.S. trade barriers
to its exports.
</P>
<P>
"There is no greater opportunity or challenge for U.S. foreign
policy than to encourage China's integration as a fully
responsible member of the international system," said Albright,
who accompanied President Clinton in his recent visit to China.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that restricting Chinese exports to the U.S. might
well cause China to devalue its currency with potentially dire
consequences for its neighbors, for China's own stability and for
markets worldwide including the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Denial of China's MFN could also hurt the U.S. exports, hike
U.S. consumer prices, set back China's economic reforms and damage
Hong Kong, and jeopardize China's cooperation on political issues
like non-proliferation, she warned.
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky also believed that the MFN status is nothing but
normal trade relations that virtually all U.S. trading partners
enjoy.
</P>
<P>
"Normal trade relations are a fundamental part of engagement,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Senator William V, Roth, the committee chairman, shared the
belief, saying "Normal trade relations are the key to our
continued dialogue with China."
</P>
<P>
Senator Connie Mack and several other committee members,
critical of China and the administration's China policy,
acknowledged that they do not have the enough votes to stop the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
Even Mike Jendrzejaczyk of Human Rights Watch, who regularly
criticizes China on human rights issue, said:"We believe that
trade and economy engagement can be a catalyst to promote greater
openness and change from within China."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, concerns were voiced about the spiraling U.S. trade
deficit with China. According to U.S. statistics, the trade
imbalance reached nearly 50 billion U.S. dollars last year and is
heading toward 60 billion dollars this year. However the Chinese
figures are much smaller.
</P>
<P>
Albright called the deficit "deeply troubling," saying "it
cannot keep growing indefinitely." Barshefsky called on China to
move more quickly to meet the terms for joining the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
China wants to join the WTO as a developing country, but the
U.S. says that its economy is too large.
</P>
<P>
China's IMF has been debated on Capitol Hill annually in the
1990s. President Clinton and some congressmen have vowed to work
for a permanent solution to the problem, but it might take
time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
