<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa's Deputy President Meets Nigerian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy President Thabo
Mbeki met with Nigerian new leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar
Thursday, saying that he was very assured about the Nigerian
government's commitment to a rapid transition to democracy.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki's visit is the first of its kind by a South African
leader since 1995. Relations between the two leading African
nations got strained by Nelson Mandela's strong criticism of
Nigeria's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, who was speaking to the press after his meeting with
Abubakar, said his government is very concerned with the
situation in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He said he listened to Abubakar's perspective of the country's
political future and was very assured about the military
government's commitment to a rapid transition to democracy.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa will make response after formal
announcement is made by the Nigerian government.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, who arrived in Nigeria Thursday, may meet some pressure
groups in Nigeria, according to a report by the Nigerian
Television Authority, quoting South African sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
